Megauploads Current Situation Megaupload was shut down by the FBI in January 2012, when the U.S Department of Justice charged them for violating piracy laws after the Motion Picture Association of America claims that most of the content transferred over the site violated U.S. copyright laws[2]. Dotcom and several company members were accused as being part of the "the 'Mega Conspiracy, a worldwide criminal organization whose members engaged in criminal copyright infringement and money laundering on a massive scale with estimated harm to copyright holders well in excess of $500 million and reported income of $175 million [2].Four individuals, including Dotcom, were arrested in the country of New Zealand. To this day, Dotcom has been fighting extradition and appears to be losing. The FBI claims Mr. Dotcom's Megaupload site earned millions of dollars by facilitating illegal file-sharing. Dotcoms lawyers told New Zealand's Supreme Court on Monday it was never meant to encourage copyright breaches [3]. However, Dotcom faces several charges such as copyright infringement, money laundering, racketeering and wire fraud, which give the potential of a long jail term if extradited and found guilty. Civil or Criminal Matter While it is apparent that Dotcom violated several criminal laws in the United States, it is not that simple. Laws are not always the same in every country, which is something Dotcoms lawyers have been using for their clients defense for the last 8 years. In New Zealand, copyright infringement is deemed to be a civil matter, not a criminal one. This made it take quite some time for New Zealand to determine that Dotcom should be extradited, since their country generally has no precedent for it when it comes to violating piracy laws. This situation shows us how governments need to have a set of universal laws among them. Because Dotcom is in New Zealand, he has the convincing argument that he did not break their laws and therefore is innocent because U.S. laws should not apply to something he did in another country. If a set of universal laws were agreed upon to regulate the actions taken by these companies, then situations such as this one wouldnt arise that could be subject to legal technicalities that would allow the company in question a free pass. If international copyright laws existed, a company with enough wealth could not relocate to another country to get away with illegal activities, because they would be illegal no matter where they went. This would stop these wealthy companies from unethical business practices and make this predicament easier on society in general. Positive and Negative Aspects of File Sharing In a society where technology is constantly advancing, it is obvious that file sharing has been useful. It allows an individual to access virtually anything online with the click of a button, a convenience that is appealing to many. Many people justify file sharing for several reasons. One is, of course, money. Why waste money on a CD with only one or two good songs when you can simply download the songs you like, free of charge? Why pay entertainment companies inflated prices for something you can simply get for free at home? People can also justify the use of file sharing by claiming that an artist gets publicity from it, an individual could access their music for free and then make the determination of whether or not they like it enough to purchase it. While all of these positive aspects of file sharing seem appealing, we must remember that while the material you are accessing may not cost you money, it always costs somebody something. A person may be able to access an artists work for free and maybe they end up liking it, but what incentive is there for the individual to go out and purchase the works they just found for free? People may not realize it, but this is considered stealing. While file sharing is not considered illegal, it does qualify as copyright infringement. Even if an individual doesnt know about this law or the fact that the file they downloaded was made available to the public without permission, you can still be penalized as ignorance of the law isnt deemed an excuse for breaking it. You are using somebodys material or intellectual property and are not paying them for it. Not only does this hurt the artist involved, it also effects the music industry they work for. If they are not making a profit off of the artists they sign and record, why bother making music at all? Another negative effect people do not think about is the lack of security involved in file sharing. Whenever an individual downloads files from an insecure website or a peer-to-peer program they are running the risk that their computer could become infected with malware and viruses, which could ironically cause them to lose all of the files on their hard drive. So, there are significant risks that make the use of file sharing less appealing. Conclusion File sharing has provided society with several benefits as the world advances, but they do not come without a price. While it provides the world with convenient access to a multitude of files, we must ask ourselves if it is always worth the cost and is done ethically. File sharing must be monitored closely and used for the benefit of society while not causing individuals harm or loss and must be done with proper regulation and ethical business practices, something that Megaupload sadly fell short of. If we can succeed in this endeavor we can provide individuals with access to large amounts of knowledge that can only lead to our advancement, and we can all reap the rewards. References References

Janiece Mary Padilla In the technology industry businesses are linked to copyright laws, in several ways these relations can be affected and lead to unfavorable outcomes. Copyright infringement is one of the greatest problems faced in the industry of technology and entertainment. People need to understand what copyright laws are and know how their lives can be impacted by illegal acts such as copyright infringement. It is important to recognize that copyright infringement will impact the way businesses interact with customers and government organizations. For example, the controversial case involving Megaupload and the founder Kim Schmitz will be analyzed to demonstrate how copyright infringement affects those involved. Negative rights and positive rights of this case will be discussed from an ethical point of view. The two key issues to be addressed are how the founders reputation was influenced by the results of the case and what authorities should do when industry leaders participate in illegal activities such as copyright infringement. These narratives will help analyze copyright infringement and how it impacted the case of Megaupload and its creator. Some correlations can be drawn between different scenarios and this case, which can provide a simple viewpoint on how infringement of copyright impacts corporations, government agencies, and consumers. The case involving Megaupload and its creator Kim Schmitz has gone through highs and lows. This particular case has gained national attention with the founder Kim Schmitz known as Dotcom fighting deportation to the United States because of his actions.[1] The creator of the infamous Megaupload file sharing website has been trying to appeal this ruling and has been adamant that the website allowed people to upload files to the cloud and at the time only small files could be attached to emails. This is an admission to what the website was meant to do according to the founder. From an ethical point of view, because he had these negative rights, Kim "Dotcom" was empowered to build a website with the ability to exchange files and not have interference with government agencies. If the situation is seen from this angle, then he exercised his liberty by creating this website and he was okay to do so. When the government stopped the use of the website and its content, his negative rights were violated. The positive rights here are the government's obligation to prevent the use of the website. The website caused significant losses to businesses in the entertainment industry. In general, work was copied and circulated illegally, and this was notappropriatebehaviorfor the government to have promoted. This view outweighs his negative rights because ultimately, he was harming businesses and breaking laws. All of the businesses involvedworked hard to get their content available on the market and it was not right for someone to benefit from their work simply because the opportunity was there. In the technology sector, Kim "Dotcom" can be seen as a pioneer, and a criminal at the same time. He was able to influence others because the industry had a loophole. It is a case that has been seen around the world, and one that has been popular because his website was very popular on the internet at one instance. Kim Schmitzs attitude is surprising, he was able to launch Mega.nz a new site that has the ability to provide encoded unidentified cloud storage while this case was ongoing. In cases that deal with copyright infringement, government departments around the world should hold people responsible for facilitating criminal activity. The government should also hold the people accountable; it is not fair to all of the parties involved. In this situation there are people involved in these activities that are not held responsible. Fines for the leaders should be considered in court andthe users that actively participated in the act should be subjected to a small penalty. Certainly, punishment willvarybetween countries, all countrieshave different lawsregarding the internet and copyrighthence interpretations around the world would be different. Copyright infringement not only extends to cyber-related industries but may also occur in art-related industries. For example, there have been cases that relate to artwork being copied or mimicked between artists. Sometimes these cases result in the defendants actions not being qualified as fair use.[3] For something to be considered fair use there are four factors to consider, and when the case involving the Barack Obama poster went to court, they determined the nature of use of the photograph that was copied. This case presented a unique outlook into how paying homage to another persons art can be a delicate matter if done without permission. This event is comparable to the Megaupload case presented above, since the parties did not have the owner's permission to copy or share the content ultimately both cases resulted in the individual being wrong. [3] According to AP News the Fairey versus The Associated Press case resulted in sentencing for the individual involved. A photograph taken was misused and distributed and resulted in unfavorable outcomes for the artist. This simple example is similar to the Megaupload case because the person involved also benefited from the work that was copied and did not give recognition to the original creator. This shows that regardless of what type of industry someone is in copyright rules always apply and the original creators of the work should be cited. In conclusion, violation of copyright is a serious matter that results in consequences for the parties involved. Governments can issue punishments or consequences that may vary depending on the circumstance and location of incidence at the time. In every situation that involves copyright infringement the truth and facts will be recognized and reflect in the outcome. In the industry of technology and entertainment, individuals and governments are all affected by the actions of an individual and those involved. It is important to take notes of cases like the one mentioned above as they can provide great insight on how copyright works in different industries. Ultimately, Kim Schmitz was not extradited to the United States however his case will be always be important because it provides the perspectives of all the parties involved when dealing with a situation as such. Copyright infringement should always be taken seriously, and originality must be highlighted in every work that is done. Individuals that partake in illegal activities should always be held accountable for their actions. As the industry grows there is more hope in knowing that individuals will strive to do the right things when it comes to copyright infringement. Functions Megaupload is the leading provider of online storage and web hosting services. People can enjoy cheap and convenient online storage, upload, and download services on Megaupload. Millions of people from all walks of life in many countries are using it. Students, professional businessmen, mothers, doctors, plumbers, insurance salesmen, mortgage brokers. Its user base is very broad, so it has a large market. Negative impact Megaupload has encroached on the interests of many people. In January 2012 Dotcom and six other executives of Megaupload were indicted in an American court on five counts of to commit racketeering, copyright infringement, and . (Erik, 2012) The site allows people to share resources publicly. If the downloaded movie is used for other commercial purposes, there will be more losses. Every movie is owned by the copyright owner, and movie theaters and online viewing sites legally buy movie rights. The advertised websites of The 'content hosting site, Megaupload.com, is advertised as having more than one billion visits to The site, more than 150 million registered users, Fifty million daily visitors and accounting for four percent of the total traffic on the Internet. The harm caused by the Conspiracy's criminal conduct to copyright holders is well in excess of $500 million. The conspirators allegedly earned more than $175 million in illegal profits through advertising revenue and selling premium memberships. (Office of public Affairs, 2012) In addition to its impact on studio revenues, Megaupload also affects the order of the film market. According to the statistics, online sales and rentals of films have increased by 6-10% since Megaupload was closed. It is a new illegal way to share movie resources on the Internet, so people may also reduce the number of times to go to the cinema. Advantages The fact that the site has such a large customer base suggests that it has a strong appeal. It makes it easier for people to see the movies they want to see and spend less money on them. The site is great for users, and it exists as an alternative to watching movies in some traditional ways. In addition, people can search through this website to find some movie resources that are not easy to find. It's like a movie that has been cut in some places or not shown publicly. It also includes pornographic and violent films, which are banned in many places. This is a new way of media, just like Tik Tok is changing the way media works now. In new media, interpersonal communication, mass communication and mass communication show a trend of integration and integration of multiple functions. Due to the convergence of media, the information transmission of new media is characterized by high speed, high quality, excessive quantity, diversification and wide range. The introduction and extensive use of a new media can reconstruct a series of situations, change people's lives and thoughts, and require a series of new social and economic behaviors. Character evaluation Megaupload broke traditional boundaries and created a popular new approach. The success of the site is enough to show that it exists as expected. This website provides a good sharing platform to meet people's needs. Seeing the popularity of the site at the time was enough to show that it was not a mistake. But the only problem is the infringement on the interests of the film studios. It's like a farmer's hard-earned crops being eaten by pesky birds. For the crew and actors who have struggled to make films, this is not what they want to see. For this reason, and because the number of users of the site is still growing, Megaupload must be legally sanctioned. Dotcom is a very brave man because he knew how it would turn out. People can also make money from the site, as long as the number of hits and download rates reach a certain level, they can make money from it. So, it's a great experience for users. Internet piracy Computer users and Internet service providers shall bear the corresponding civil liability for infringing the civil rights and interests of the state, the collective or others through the Internet. In recent years, with the rapid development of the network era, many new problems are becoming more and more prominent. In China, although a series of relevant laws and regulations, judicial interpretations and administrative rules have been successively issued by the legislative branch to regulate online behaviors and protect citizens' legal rights in the online environment to some extent. However, compared with the ever-changing situation of network development, there are still many deficiencies in the existing laws concerning network infringement. With the rapid development and popularization of the Internet, it is urgent to formulate relevant laws and regulations to regulate all kinds of Internet behaviors. Strengthen the training of professional personnel In addition to legal means, the application of advanced technical means is also indispensable to control network infringement. In order to better protect civil rights, effectively prevent the occurrence of network infringement, the complexity of network infringement puts forward higher requirements for network management talents. More interdisciplinary talents with legal knowledge, professional computer and network management are needed. To make a large number of compound information network management talents stand out in the cause of information network play a strong force. Conclusion In general, Megaupload has now been sanctioned by the law for being an illegal site. Legal and moral considerations should be considered before interests. Although it is illegal, it has a large number of users and a wide market. This shows that this is a trend of media platform development but need to pay attention to more network security incidents. Openness and freedom are the charm of the Internet. But, as George Bernard Shaw said, "Freedom means responsibility! A free, democratic, and rule-of-law society is the result of the coexistence and complementarity between individual freedom and public responsibility. Kim Schmitz: Hero or Criminal? Jason Yuan Dr. Vladimir Kuperman ICSI 300Z Societal and Ethical implications of Computing Fall 2020 October 26th, 2020 Page 1

Kim Schmitz is a German internet entrepreneur who was and is the founder of notorious internet websites or cyberlockers known as Megaupload or mega.nz. The original, now defunct website Megaupload reportedly generated more than $100 million in business revenues and both websites can be cited as examples of websites on the internet where piracy takes place. After Megaupload was eventually terminated for violating these copyright infringement laws, Kim started a new business and website called simply mega in 2013 but later severed ties with the company in 2015. As of today, Mega is still up and running as intended and is a site that I actually have used myself semi frequently for legal file sharing activities. At the peak of its popularity, Megaupload was estimated to be the 13th most popular website on the internet and was responsible for 4% of all internet traffic. On the 5th of January in 2012, the United States filed an indictment against Kim Dotcom and other executives at Megaupload for crimes such as racketeering, copyright infringement, and conspiracy to money laundering. Kim was later arrested in an armed raid and nearly all of his assets were confiscated and his bank accounts were frozen. Since distancing himself from the internet cyberlocker world and his own mega, Kim has been in and out of court multiple times, as well as dabbling in a music career, recording and releasing a studio album titled Good Times. In this situation, there are some negative and positive rights involved. In the case of the copyright situation a negative right would be that someone has the negative right to download the content that is illegally uploaded to a site like Megaupload until something is done to stop them such as being caught doing the activity via copyright law, and a positive right would be the right of governments to punish those who violate these same copyright laws. As someone who has been using the internet for their whole life, I feel pretty well informed on how much of a gray area, both morally and legally the fair use and copyright world can be. I personally am of the opinion that in most cases, copyright infringement is a victimless crime, particularly when the material in question is from a larger corporation, such as if someone were to pirate a game from a AAA developer that notoriously treats its employees poorly. However, if someone were to do this to an independent studio I would see that as an immoral act to carry out. With that being said, I do understand how this view could be seen as hypocritical or self serving to make one feel better about illegally pirating content on the internet. With that being said the question that is asked is whether or not Kim Dotcom is a hero, a criminal, or something in between. As far as the law is concerned, Kim is certainly a criminal. The Federal Bureau of Investigation seized the domain to Megaupload. To some of the most extreme people on the internet, he could be hailed as a hero, as seen with hacker group Anonymous reacting to the seizure of megaupload by hitting the Department of Justice, among other organizations such as the RIAA (Recording Industry Association of America) and MPAA (Motion Picture Association) as well as the Universal Music Group with a Denial of Service attack. but in my opinion he is neither. Dotcom was a man with an idea for a website that happened to blow up in the way that it did, Both Megaupload and Mega.nz do have legitimate, legal applications but however are obviously most notorious for the fact that they are used for the sharing of illegally obtained media. As someone who has been around on the internet long enough to have used both, Kims websites have certainly saved me a lot of time and I feel overall he left a positive impact on the internet age. While yes, through these websites he severely violated copyright law and cost businesses multiple hundreds of millions of dollars in revenue, his legacy and impact on the internet will likely be felt forever, especially with Mega.nz prevailing and still being a widely used website on the internet. As of September 2020 according to similarweb.com , Mega.nz is the 171st most popular website on the internet. A far drop from Megaupload peaking at #13, but still clearly a very important website on todays world wide web. Another question that must be asked is that to what extent should governments, be that domestic or foreign hold people responsible the facilitation of illegal activity? In my opinion, governments themselves have a right to uphold copyright law, and protect any and all intellectual property, so they should not only be doing this via terminating instances of stolen intellectual property, but if say for example a government was facilitating these said illegal activities, then on an international scale they should be held accountable for the same crimes that they would be doing things as high level as a full on armed raid of Kim Dotcoms house complete with helicopters. A non cyber analogy to this copyright infringement scenario could be from Kanye Wests 2010 album My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy regarding the song Blame Game which contains a re-recording of a sample from Aphex Twins Avril 14th. Kanye and his team reportedly used this sample for the track without much contact or permission from Aphex Twin and they were allegedly fairly rude throughout the process as well, telling Aphex Its not yours, its ours, and were not even asking you anymore. Despite all of this, The matter never went to court and Avril 14 and Aphex Twin both ultimately ended up receiving the credit that they were due within the credits of the record. Much like downloading shared content on the internet and changing it however you so please, sampling music works much in the same way and the original creator of what you are sampling is always entitled to being credited on your record if you are working with their own art. In conclusion, while Kim Dotcoms Megaupload and Mega.nz obviously have their vast majority of legal problems, such as essentially robbing many companies of hundreds of millions of dollars in revenue due to its websites being used for illegal pirating activities however, I feel that these websites have also brought a lot of good to the internet, and do have genuine, legal uses with no mal intent and have personally been very helpful websites for me in the past. In the eyes of the law Kim is obviously no doubt a criminal, however in my eyes he is simply just a normal guy who made a website, that was also used for that purpose. Despite this, I obviously do understand if someone were to feel that Kim, for his actions of allowing these illegal activities to take place had compromised his morals, as an unaffected consumer and someone who sometimes find myself on the site I personally am rather unbothered.

The online world is a tricky place when it comes to how laws in different countries interact. With the newfound potential for anyone located in one place to easily break laws in another place without setting foot there, many of the details surrounding how to handle these cases have yet to be fully fleshed out. The situation surrounding the company Megaupload is a great example of this clash between the laws of different governments. Founded in 2005 by entrepreneur Kim Dotcom, Megaupload was at one point the 13th most popular website on the internet, garnering 4% of online traffic worldwide [1]. It was essentially a digital storage unit that was frequently used to hold photos, videos, and audio. Megauploads business model relied on two sources of income. First there was premium subscriptions that allowed users fast access and distribution of the data the user stored on their servers and second were advertisements [2]. It was estimated by the US Government that Megaupload had made $175 million over the course of their operation, with approximately $150 million from premium users and $25 million form advertisements [3][2]. In 2012, they were indicted by the FBI who claimed the company was illegally contributing to the infringement of copyright material protected by US law [1]. While the sites purpose was not specifically hold illegal content, a large part of its userbase was known to be uploading and distributing pirated material [2]. The FBI also claimed that the site was responsible for $500 million in losses to the music and film industries [1]. Kim Dotcom and his other co-founder, Mathias Ortmann were arrested in a raid of Dotcomss Auckland mansion and subsequently incarcerated [1][3]. After a month, Dotcom was released on bail [3]. In order to understand this case any further, it is important to know what safe harbor is. As someone who hosts a site on the internet, you are not necessarily liable for all of the information on your platform as long as you meet some key requirements [4]. In this context, safe harbor generally means that as long as a company adheres to a set of guidelines that dictate how they handle illegal content on their platform, they are protected from being held liable for that content [4]. The problem lies in that the rules that qualify a company for safe harbor depend on where you are. In the Megaupload case, the United States has safe harbor as it is defined under the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA) and in New Zealand, the country in which the founder of Megaupload resides, there are a different (but similar) set of rules for safe harbor defined in the Harmful Digital Communications Act (HDCA) [4][5]. Where safe harbor comes into play in the Megaupload case is in the fight to extradite Dotcom to the United States from New Zealand to be tried for the indictments from the FBI. As of now, Dotcom is still in New Zealand fighting his extradition to the United States. Dotcom claims that the actions of Megaupload were not criminal offences in NZ and therefore cannot be extradited [1]. Dotcom and his lawyers also deny the charges against him and claim the company complied with both the DMCA and HDCA definitions of safe harbor [3]. However, the FBI claims, among other things, that Megaupload incentivized the uploading of copyrighted material through their Uploader Rewards Program in which premium users were paid for uploading popular content [2]. This case is currently waiting to be heard in the New Zealand Supreme Court after being ruled in lower courts that there is a case for extradition [6]. Dotcom has said in a Tweet dated October 25th 2020 that he anticipates the ruling that he should be extradited be upheld and that if this does happen, he will pursue taking his case to international court [7]. Understanding the positive and negative rights in this scenario will help to really dissect what is going on here. Entities within the United States have the positive right to have their intellectual property protected by the government. The US is fulfilling this positive right by attempting to extradite Dotcom to the United States to be held accountable for the damage that Megaupload has done to the music and film industry. The United States government itself has the negative right to request the extradition of Dotcom as well as prosecute him to the fullest extent of the law (domestic and international). A New Zealand citizen, in this case Kim Dotcom, has the negative right to a fair extradition hearing as well as a fair trial if extradited to the United States. No ones actions are entirely good or bad. In fact, the same can be said when it comes to their intentions. Everyone falls somewhere in between, and Kim Dotcom is no exception. However, when reviewing documents of the FBIs indictment of Dotcom, it seems he falls closer to the side of wrongdoing in the case of Megaupload. In the FBIs investigation of the company they found that those who worked at Megaupload not only knew of the illegal content distributed on the site, but actually contributed to the upload and distribution of illegal works [2]. They not only incentivized the uploading of illegal content monetarily but by making the length of storage a function of how popular the uploaded content is [2]. Megaupload also seemed to mask the discovery of copyrighted material from the copyright holder by not having a search function on the site [2]. The only way to access a certain file is via the link, meaning if you didnt have the link, youd never know the file is there [2]. This direct link system also leads to problems implementing DMCA takedowns as instead of removing the actual copyright content stored on their site, just the link would be removed [2]. Many other good points were made by the FBI in the indictment of Dotcom; however, it is important to keep in mind that this is only the indictment and therefore only one side of the argument. It is hard to imagine that Kim Dotcom could change my mind on his wrongdoing in this case but it would be dishonest to come to a conclusive decision before a proper trial has happened between him and the FBI in which all the evidence on both sides is in display. At the end of the day, governments have a duty to protect their citizens. Whether it be their citizens physical property, intellectual property or otherwise, they must do what they can within their own laws and international laws to make sure that those who jeopardize the right of their citizens are prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law. This same principle can be applied to non-cyber situations as well. Lets say there is a bank (anywhere in the world), and this bank took money from people who were obtaining it through sources that are illegal in the United States (such as drug cartels) and this bank was only adhering to the bare minimum actions they needed to take. For example, if in order to do this under the radar all they had to do was report a suspicious deposit but werent necessarily required to do anything about it. And that the acceptance of this money directly harmed the United States by allowing these cartels to essentially launder their money. This is actually speculated to be one of the ways Jeffery Epstein operated somewhat legally for years.

Kim Dotcom is the creator of the site once known as Megaupload and later the site MEGA. These two sites were/are (respectively) file sharing sites with full encryption for users. The services that Kim Dotcom provided resulted in issues that spanned many different topics in this class, including ethics, privacy, freedom of speech, and copyright. Kim Dotcom is an internet entrepreneur. He innovated many things in the internet age. He claims he created two-factor authentication and was awarded a patent for it, he pioneered Flash animation and also invented a way to do video conferencing over a cell phone in 1999, when cell phones werent even commonplace (McGuire). He has a track record of innovation, but also a track record of criminal activity. The following excerpt from a Motherboard article about him lists just some of the legal trouble he had been in even before the invention of Megaupload: In March of 1994, he was arrested by police for trafficking in stolen phone calling card numbers. He was held in custody for a month, then arrested again on additional hacking charges shortly afterward and again released. In 1998, he was convicted of 11 counts of computer fraud, 10 counts of data espionage, and an assortment of other charges. He received a two-year suspended sentencebecause, at just 20, he was declared "under age" at the time the crimes were committed. (Gallagher) This however shouldnt be held against him in the current case he has against him with Megaupload and the services it provided and facilitated. The fact of the matter is that while many copyrighted materials were illegally shared on Megaupload, that that wasnt his sole intention with the site. He was just the middleman who provided a service for people to use however they liked. That would be analogous to shutting down the post service because people are sending drugs in the mail or just conducting some other kind of illegal activity through the mail, something which Dotcom noted in his interview on Vice. The current situation with Dotcom is that he has still not been extradited to the U.S. where they want to charge him for all the crimes they have against him. He has been living in New Zealand for a decade, ever since the charges against him for Megaupload led him to flee Hong Kong where he had been living previously. The U.S. government has been trying to extradite him from New Zealand ever since and has not been able to yet. While New Zealands courts have said that there are grounds for extradition, the decision must ultimately then be handed over to the Supreme Court for the final decision. The most recent update I could find on the state of the case, from August of this year, states that: Dotcom admitted that he expects to lose the Supreme Court case. Because, he said, three of the judges are biased as a result of them being appointed by ministers allied to the countrys National Party, which was in power when NZ and US officials collaborated on shutting down MegaUpload and arresting Dotcom et al back in 2012. (Cooke) Kim Dotcom has been very active on Twitter in the last couple of months given that it is election time and he has been pretty involved in politics since his legal battles, and with the increase in online presence has come more information on his case, like the information above. Even though he has shared more information on the case, it seems like its still at the same standstill that it was before, essentially, with the only difference being that now he is waiting on the Supreme Courts ruling. The topic of who is at fault and who should be held responsible in cases such as these are not black and white, they are quite hard to figure considering there are so many parties involved and people with different intentions with such a service. While I can certainly see both sides of the argument, with one side being that Kim Dotcom should be held responsible for all the illegal copyright infringing activity happening on his platform, and the other being that he is just the provider of the service and that he should not be held responsible; I have to say that I side with the latter judgement. Kim Dotcom is really just a tech innovator, he knew that encryption was important and wanted to create a file sharing service where users could share files with said encryption. He was quite ahead of the curve with being acutely aware of the way the government can and does track civilians, i.e. Edward Snowdens whistleblowing on the NSA. It makes sense for him to be more aware than the general public since he does exist in the cybersecurity space, but nonetheless, it was a rather new kind of service being offered on such a widescale platform that so many people were accessing. Its really no fault of Dotcoms that his site got used for the sharing of copyrighted materials, and in turn most likely impacted those industries so for him to be held responsible for other peoples individual actions really doesnt make sense. Prohibition is a tactic that has never really worked, we saw it with alcohol in the past and with illegal drugs today which are still available if people want to get access to them. Where theres a will theres a way, so if hes not the one providing the service then most likely someone else will step up and fill that demand. The government is spending so much time on someone that is not even a threat to anybody or anything, meanwhile that time and those resources could be better put to tracking down or persecuting actual criminals who are a threat in some way, shape, or form, whether it be to others, or an industry, or people whose sole purpose is to share copyrighted materials (like PirateBay and other torrenting sites). To sum everything up, Kim Dotcom is a tech innovator who has had legal troubles for a long time, but especially since the creation of Megaupload. While he hasnt yet been extradited, it seems like that the final decision on this is in its final stages, having to go through New Zealands Supreme Court, but even then, subject to appeal. While many copyrighted materials were shared on Megaupload, the burden of responsibility shouldnt fall directly on someone who just simply provided the service, because as I stated before, thats like shutting down the post office because illegal materials are being sent through the mail. His case has many parallels with almost everything we have learned thus far in class and it is interesting to see something that crosses as many topics as this one does, as the deciding what is the correct judgement to make in cases like these isnt always easy, since a lot of ethics comes down to individual perspective.

Megaupload was an internet service that was established in 2005 by internet entrepreneur Kim Dotcom. This webservice allowed the file sharing, storage and viewing of copyrighted material. At one point it was claimed to have over one hundred and fifty million users with a fifty million concurrent users and was the thirteenth most visited site on the internet. [1] On this website you could find copyrighted material such as movies, television shows, books, music and software. And as you could imagine this is where the controversy arose. Seeing as what this website was doing was illegal, in 2012 police had raided his mansion and arrested him and others. Since then the United States government has been trying to extradite Kim to account for the criminal charges they have brought to light. And if he ever does get extradited, the music and movie industries still are looking to pursue charges. [2] Since there are numerous court cases and decisions to be made, it is a very tricky process. While that has been going on, in 2013 Kim has launched mega.nz which is a cloud-storage and file hosting service. Overall it is a very user friendly, reputable and most importantly legal service. He was so confident in this new creation that he went as far to tweet: "I'll be the first tech billionaire who got indicted, lost everything and created another billion-dollar tech company while on bail." Mega upload sparked a huge debate on the negative and positive rights involved in the copyright infringement. Positive rights are the freedom to something, while negative rights are the freedom from something. As we the common people have the positive right to listen to music, watch movies and television. These industries corporative have the negative right of the intellectual property. Megaupload was a creation that has sent a series of want to bes into effect. But I still take the side of the industries that were ripped off. Although one could argue that Megaupload was a great example to show the severity that these types of sites have on who they are stealing from. Kim Dotcom has proven that it can and will be done and that there are going to be massive repercussions. If in the lifespan of his creation he was able to generate as much money as he did, and cost industries as much as he did, I could not imagine what the thousands of other sites are costing. These industries were stolen from, but they were also shown what an impact like this can have on themselves if they are not careful. Specifically, in the movie industry, many people view their movies from a pirated website, and that is stealing from ticket and digital sales. But we can also see how the negative rights of these companies is being violated and there does not seem to be much to do about it. There needs to be a more effective way to be able to identify when people violate these laws. I believe that Kim Dotcom is not necessarily a criminal, but he is definitely not a hero. These days pirated movies, television shows, music and live video content such as sports are everywhere over the web. There are numerous websites that provide such content. Dealing with sites like these are like dealing with weeds, if you shut it down, two more emerge. And because the government does not take as big a stance against these individuals as they do with Kim Dotcom, that is why I would not call him a criminal. But that does not make him a hero. What he did was morally and ethically wrong. It was said that he had cost film studios and record labels more than five-hundred million dollars. But when it comes to people facilitating illegal content, it does not seem there is a whole lot that governments can do to hold them responsible. Since there are so many types of websites facilitating different types of copyrighted material and that these websites are not generally tied to a specific individual, it makes it near impossible to locate the source. Which is why if and when the site goes down, if they do not already have another one live, it is only a matter of time before they do. Discussing copyright infringement outside of the cyber world, we would be looking at anything where you copy someone elses work without getting consent from that individual. I feel like these days when people hear copyright infringement, they think of something to do with the web just because the world is shifting to a cyber age. But people fail to neglect that there are other examples of such outside cyber space. A small-scale example of this could be a student or author who copys off another source without giving credit or consent from the author. Another example of this could be people selling these movies or music. You can walk the streets of New York City and find people selling rip offs of jewelry, handbags, and pirated movies. And that is really no different than people doing this on the web, the only real difference is that the people on the street do not have the anonymity as the people on the web. And it is this reason alone why copyright infringement is more widely seen on the web. When it comes to the topic of intellectual property and copyright infringement the question of ethics comes into play. Like I stated before there are thousands of sites out there that offer illegal streaming of movies, television shows, music, live video content, etcetera. And although some of them get taken down, most of them do not. And it is very mind blowing how people can do this and get away with it. And for these people that do operate these sites there is nothing that ties them directly to it and which is the problem. That most of these industries have to rely on the people to operate ethically. Kim Dotcom is just one example of this and was put in the spotlight for it. But there are thousands of people like him out there that are not as scrutinized as him. So that is why I believe that he is not a criminal nor a hero. But because he did make millions of his site, I believe he should have to pay a hefty fine not be jailed for it. I remember when I was younger that there was this website where people were able to watch illegal streamed movies, and to this day it is still up and functioning. I do not believe that there is an efficient way to stop this sort of thing from happening, seeing as it already exists on a large scale. I believe that Kim Dotcom has shown this and that the government it too caught up in wanting to extradite and charge him that they are failing to take notice to the thousands who are getting away with the same crime as him.

There has never been a time in history where information has been so widely available as it is today. When the internet was created the intent was to allow scientists to share information in a fast and reliable way globally. As the potential of the internet began to be realized the sharing of other goods and services became popular. It was only a matter of time before the internet became a powerful tool that companies use to sell music and movies to consumers. The companies were not the only ones with access to this powerful tool and individuals with computing knowledge had the power to share and access information without paying for it. However, the age old proverb of, with great power comes great responsibility, for many was lost and the law started catching up to those that were illegally accessing commercial content. One such case is that of Kim Schmitz Dotcom and his once greatly successful cloud service Megaupload that was shutdown by The United States Government. We will take a closer look at Kim Dotcoms story, rights, and motives to better understand if Mr. Dotcom truly is a criminal. The story begins in 2005 when European entrepreneur Kim Dotcom created a website known as Megaupload. From the years 2005-2012 the website became widely popular as a cloud storage service that allowed users to save files such as movies and music to the cloud. This same business model of cloud storage is widely used today, however, Mr. Dotcoms website allowed users to share their saved files through a link that could be sent to other users. In later years this effectively created a platform for piracy because it allowed for the sharing of copyrighted material freely. This is where the major point of contention begins. In a statement on Twitter, Mr. Dotcom states that, In 2005 I created a website that allowed people to upload files to the cloud. At the time only small files could be attached to emails. Megaupload allowed users to email a link to a file. Thats it. [1] The limited ability of the internet at the time meant that the website did not begin as a platform for piracy thus what the website evolved into was a product of technological advances. The U.S. Government, however, was not interested in the humble beginnings of Mr. Dotcoms website, rather, what if had become when in 2012 they shut down Megaupload and worked with the authorities in New Zealand to raid his permanent estate. The accusations against Mr. Dotcom included, conspiracy to commit racketeering, copyright infringement, money laundering and wire fraud. [1] The raid in 2012 was only the beginning and has led to an almost decade long battle between Mr. Dotcom and The U.S. Government to have him extradited to the U.S. for prosecution. During this time Mr. Dotcom has filed lawsuits against both the New Zealand and U.S. governments for, $6.8 billion in damages for his loss of business, investments and reputation. [2] With both sides putting up a fight and the final appeal still in the courts we have to ask, who is truly in the right in this particular case? In order to help determine which side of this case is in the right the ideologies of positive and negative rights can be applied. To start we will examine Mr. Dotcoms Megaupload through the lens of negative rights. According to the author of The Gift of Fire, Sara Baase, The only obligation negative rights impose on other people is that they may not prevent you from acting. [3] Through this lens we can say that Mr. Dotcom had the negative right to create a website that allows for people to upload files to a cloud. The negative rights of the people who used this service was to upload content that they wished to and share a link to that file so that others may access those files whether or not they are copyright material or not. Mr. Dotcom also therefore was not at fault for what the users posted because he was not the one who was personally distributing the illegal content. By negative rights he is protected from prosecution as the information being shared was encrypted and did not allow for him to know when laws were being broken by users. Sara Baase also writes on positive rights saying they, impose an obligation on some people to provide certain things for others. [3] Therefore, governments under positive rights have the ability to stand up for companies that have lost money because they believe Megaupload allowed for piracy to happen. Positive rights also allows for the U.S. Government to fight for the ability to recoup monetary losses that were incurred as well as punishing those that aided in illegal activity to deter others from doing so in the future. With a better understanding of where each side of the argument is coming from in regards to negative and positive rights we can scrutinize the actions of each side and come to one possible conclusion of who is in the right. From the start it is clear that Megaupload did not begin as a website meant to undermine copyright laws. With computing power that allowed for only small files to be shared Mr. Dotcom started a business that focused on privacy and the desire to share ideas. He had every right to do this and when the technology had advanced to the point of being able to share files large enough to contain full length movies the business had already been established. Due to the nature of the internet there are multiple ways for users to share and access information that is protected by copyright. Mr. Dotcoms business just helped those that wished to break the law find a fast convenient way to do so. Even to this day criminals use websites to commit crimes and many of them are held in high regard because of their lawful uses. For example in the non-cyber circumstance of counterfeit clothing, should the company that built the factory be liable for what a company does after they buy it? Textile machines and equipment that go into building factories are highly specialized and when one company builds one they may sell it to a business who creates illegal garments when it was their belief it would be used for legal production. Its true the government does have the right to help uphold the law especially because positive rights are mainly how the modern western world functions. However, the extent the U.S. government has gone to try and prosecute Mr. Dotcom seems illegitimate. Other innovators such as Sean Parker, the creator of Napster, have created businesses of even more blatant copyright infringements and have gone unscathed. Kim Dotcom has been an innovator in the tech world and while Megaupload could have done things differently he is not the criminal he is made out to be. Due to his current situation he has moved towards privacy advocacy which is something that needs to be addressed. This doesnt make him a hero though, it may be more for show than passion because of the circumstance he has been put in. However, governments need to hold individuals accountable in a respectable fashion regardless of the supposed infractions. Illegal activity can be facilitated in a multitude of different ways and just because those who wish to act illegally find a way to exploit the system the burden should not come down on the innovator. Governments need to focus on how to cut off the economic factor of illegal activity, not the innovations of tools that may or may not allow it to take place.

Abstract The purpose of this paper is to discuss the current situation with the Megaupload, a file sharing service that was created to allow users to upload and download files to its servers. This paper will analyze the positive and negative rights involved with Megaupload and file sharing. It will address both sides of the argument but will tell you why ultimately what Megaupload did was wrong and unethical, because they committed copyright infringement and violated piracy laws. It will also discuss how Dotcom is therefore a criminal that should be penalized for his actions and the extent to which governments should hold individuals responsible for facilitating illegal activities. Introduction File sharing has become massively popular in the last decade. As technology has advanced and files have become digitized, it has become much more convenient for a consumer to make digital purchases instead of going out to a store to purchase a CD or DVD. It also provides individuals the capability to discover various forms of entertainment that is simply a click away, a much-appreciated convenience. For these reasons, many file sharing companies were founded in the last 20 years to meet this growing demand. One of the most popular file sharing services that was created was Megaupload, a Hong Kong based online company that operated from 2005 to 2012. Megaupload provided online services related to file storage and sharing [1]. While Megaupload arguably provided a convenient service to users, they used unethical methods to do so, such as violating copyright laws. This paper will discuss the current situation with Megaupload after they were accused of breaking laws. It will talk about how Megaupload violated copyright infringement and therefore the sites founder Dotcom should be subject to legal penalization. It will also discuss the extent to which governments should hold individuals such as Dotcom responsible for facilitating these illegal activities and address the positive and negative effects of file sharing.

The Megaupload, a company that provides users a place to share and store files, had been discontinued ever since the U.S. government seized its domain name on January 19, 2012. The reason for the shutdown of Megaupload and arrest of Kim Schmitz Dotcom was copyright infringement, racketeering, and money laundering. However, this cause many to rise and trigger massive SOPA protest, Stop Online Piracy Act, which many companies either stop providing services for a period of time, blacking out their logo, or voicing their opposition in some way. This should had answered to whether Kim Schmitz Dotcom and his employees should hold accountable for making the commitment of copyright infringement easily by others. Currently, Kim Schmitz Dotcom was in New Zealand with his wife, Liz Dotcom (Elizabeth Donnelly), and adopted a dog at the start of lockdown cause by COVID-19. Other then that, they are doing fine and waiting for their Judgment in appeal against finding they are eligible for extradition to the United States to be delivered in the Supreme Court Wednesday 4 November at 11am [1]. In other words, the conclusion will be on U.S. 2020 Election Day. Granted that the time difference between New York and New Zealand is 18 hours, Wednesday 4 November at 11 am in New Zealand is Tuesday 3 November at 5 pm in New York. It is possible for Election Day to outshine the case result and swept under the media. Kim Schmitz Dotcom held Joe Boden and Chris Dodd accountable for the downfall of Megaupload, mentioned in his tweet. It was elaborated that On the one hand, Joe Biden delivered to Chris Dodd the takedown of a major perceived threat to the MPAAs copyright holders; on the other hand, Chris Dodd delivered to Joe Biden the continuing political and financial support of Hollywood during the White Houses critical 2012 reelection campaign [2]. Since Joe Biden was running for presidency this year, Kim Schmitz Dotcom continuing speak out against Joe Biden in his tweets. As for his business and goals, a year after the shutdown of Megaupload, MEGA was launched, founded by the same group, and function similarity to Megaupload. However, after about a year, Kim Schmitz Dotcom had sold most of his shareholding and stepped down as a Director to pursue new goals [3]. After he step down, he created a new music streaming service called Baboom. Other than that, he focuses on gaming and stopping cyber attackers. We could use negative and positive rights as an ethical view of Megaupload takedown case. It was Megauploads positive right to provide online services on file sharing and storage. On the other hand, it is the negative right of people to create music, pictures, files, programs, and objects online to trade with others by money. Then we have the users who have the negative right to enjoy both services, which lead to the conflicts of causing the copyright infringement. To combat this, Megaupload will listen to the original owners if they want their content to be taken down. Also, under their terms and service, Megaupload will not be able to know what user stored. These terms help Megaupload to tell others that it is not their fault for users action regarding to copyright infringement and will not aid them to doing so. However, even with these defenses, Megaupload still got taken down. After the general view of Megaupload, the question that is still unanswered: should Kim Schmitz Dotcom and other Megaupload employees be hang over to the United States for trail. On my opinion, I do not see a reason for Kim Schmitz Dotcom and his partner to be on trial for crimes they did not participate in. First, they were accused of copyright infringement. The definition from Justia follows There are two types of infringement: primary and secondary. A primary infringement involves a direct infringement by the defendant. Secondary infringement happens if someone facilitates another person or group in infringing on a copyright [4]. The type of copyright infringement that opposition claimed falls on Megaupload was the secondary infringement. There are two features needed for proving a secondary infringement but proving one false should mean it is not an infringement. First, the third party intentionally or knowingly induced the infringement or provided the primary infringer with the means to commit the infringement [4]. The evidence opposition shown for this feature was The Mega Conspiracys Abuse Tool did not actually function as the copyright owners were led to believe, however, because the Abuse Tool only disabled the specific URL link identified, and the Abuse Tool failed to disable access to the underlying copyright-infringing material or remove the file from the server [5], therefore leading them to fail deleting the infringers and with intention of allowing to keep users to keep the file. However, I do not see the need to delete the file and only removing the link to share is fine. Users can use their own copy of items that they brought but should not share it with anyone. This share link feature was built in the same way as Google Drive and Dropbox. There should not be a difference for the consequences of using file sharing link program. Therefore, the copyright infringement on Megaupload was just a groundless accusation. To some, Kim Schmitz Dotcom was viewed as a hero and others as a villain. However, I do not see him as any, but a poor victim. Kim Schmitz Dotcom was a rich person and living a luxurious life. While viewing Kim Schmitz Dotcom as innocent to the Megaupload case, seeing that he got raided by police during his birthday and most of his assets are seized. It was a planned raid that timed around Dotcom's 38th birthday celebrations most of the people who were indicted (in the US) would be at his party [6]. This was unnecessary and aggressive to someone who was not proven guilty of his accusation. It was said that around 80 polices participated. Also, after bailing out of jail, only $750,000 out of $17 million of assets were returned due to some paperwork error. After all the commotion, the court ruled that the raid was invalid and overturn that decision, almost seem like they are trolling him. Also, Kim Schmitz Dotcom was spied on illegally in 2011, which violated his privacy, since he was a permanent residence and should be excuse out of Government Communications Security Bureaus surveillance. In general, it was because of such accusation that made Kim Schmitz Dotcom the victim and this cross the boundary of where government should hold people accountable for making illegal activity easier. On that matter, making illegal activity easier should not be a crime unless company intended to do so. To help separating the one who is unintentionally committing such act, government should help and come up a solution with a due date. Passing the due date will lead to terminating services until a solution was found. If the company will not accept the aid of the government, then one can say this is an intentional crime, unless the company are not aware of it. There is no need for violence like the raid, that was overkill. The whole Megaupload case was like a museum. A museum displaying other peoples work and an entrance fee. The purpose of the museum is to share the beauty with everyone. However, the owner of individual piece of object given to the museum can ask the manager to get rid of it. The museum did take it off from display but kept it in their inventory. The owner of the object was satisfied and left. However, spies or journalist came to survey and try finding some dirt on the museum. They eventually succeed and the drama unfolded about why the object was not destroyed. Eventually, the museum seized, and the sad thing was that the manager had to handle everything while outside of country. To sum up, the Megaupload case and the after effect was unethical. The Megaupload case had been dragged on for so long and it is still going to this day. The government of New Zealand had to participate and step outside of their boundaries to spy, with intend to help U.S. on Megaupload case, without thinking about their National Security. Many unfortunate events, like the mansion raid, might soon fall on Kim Schmitz Dotcom cause by a non-existed crime. Fortunately, the legacy of Megaupload was carried on by MEGA and up running without a problem.

Any Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of an organization is tasked with a number of jobs and duties. Majority of these tasks have the intention of steering the organization in a fiscally appreciative direction. This cannot be said for the founder of the organization however, a founder's position within an organization is contingent to the operational position served during the founding of the organization. The now-defunct organization Megaupload is an instance in which the CEO was also the founder and when the organization was implicated on charges of piracy by the United States Justice Department the CEO became subject to charges presented forward. The CEO of Megaupload Kim Schmitz, also known as Kim Dotcom, was brought into the charges pressed against himself and Megaupload. These charges included criminal copyright infringement, money laundering, racketeering and wire fraud. The damages include 500 million and the revenue generated by Megaupload upwards to 175 million dollars. The case itself has spanned jurisdiction within a number of countries and began 2012 all throughout to present day. The current status of the case is that CEO and Founder of Megaupload Kim Schmitz must be extradited to the United States from New Zealand. The first direct impact this had on Kim Schmitz personal life and any fiscal implications were that all assets that pertained to cash assets and frozen accounts that range from PayPal to worldwide bank accounts. The rights that were involved range from a multitude of ethical government perspectives. The positive perspectives are particularly a set of rights that had a direct impact on this situation between Kim Dotcom, Megaupload and the United States Justice Department. More specifically the first positive is the international protection of original content this situation promotes. Essentially regardless of a country's law or international laws an individual were to do something illegal, he would be the one to take the blame for it. That would lead to that party being safe and not getting caught by their violations of any kind of law. In regards to the ability for the United States to extradite an individual from the country of New Zealand, Kim Dotcoms situation is indeed peculiar. The rights that were granted to him were essentially changed as his situation with the United States Judicial Department grew. This not only led to the shutdown of Megaupload but also an indictment that charges executives of Megaupload with making $175 Million from user subscription fees and advertisements. With that being said, this also led to the Chief Executive Officers residence being raided by New Zealand Police which consisted of 76 officers and two helicopters. The total amount of assets seized on Kims property is $17 Million. In 2012 Dotcom was imprisoned in Mt Eden Prison and spent his recent years since that point defending his innocence in the cases that were brought forth upon him by the United States Justice system. Kim even states that he has spent millions of dollars on legal fees in order to ensure quality and efficient legal representation in not only New Zealand but the United States.

Kim Dotcom is a German born tech entrepreneur who has become a hot topic for copyright owners across the globe. In 2012 the United States Department of Justice ordered the site to be shut down, and in New Zealand, the site owner and a handful of other employees were [1]. Federal prosecutors announced that Dotcoms website Megaupload.com was responsible for the loss of 500 million dollars in revenue for copyright holders around the world. The site was responsible for harboring numerous files that were protected by copyrights and making them available for the public to access. This crime is known as Piracy and is the bane of content creators existence. People who create digital products want to be reimbursed for their time and work, sites like MegaUpload steal this hard-earned revenue from creators by giving people access to products without having to pay for it. It is evident that people like Kim Dotcom are criminal and pretending to not know what is hosted on their website is negligent and is not a reason to avoid prosecution for the Piracy he has allowed on his site. As of 2019, Kim Dotcom is a free man residing in New Zealand. Kim Dotcom is actively fighting the United States Department of Justice who is trying to extradite Kim into the United States where he will stand trial for his crimes. Kim Dotcoms only hope in avoiding trial lies in the New Zealand Supreme Court, who is singlehandedly responsible for deciding whether or not Kim Dotcom will be extradited to the United States for trial [2]. Kim Dotcom has taken to Twitter to define his stance on his legal situation, which he summarized in this tweet, In 2005 I created a website that allowed people to upload files to the cloud. At the time only small files could be attached to emails. Megaupload allowed users to email a link to a file. Thats it. In 2019 the NZ Supreme Court decides if I should be extradited for this crime [3]. As of today, MegaUpload company Mega Ltd. has been republished its site under the new name of MEGA. It was launched in 2013 and is currently available in 49 languages [4]. Before analyzing the legitimacy of Kim Dotcoms argument, I must define Positive and Negative rights. Negative and Positive rights can be summarized by the following quote, A negative right is a right not to be subjected to an action of another person or group; negative rights permit or oblige inaction. A positive right is a right to be subjected to an action or another person or group; positive rights permit or oblige action [5]. It is now clear that the Kim Dotcom and the United States Department of Justice each represent Negative and Positive rights, respectively. Kim Dotcom takes a stance that he simply created a site that allowed people to store files in the cloud, and that it is not his fault that people used this service to host copyrighted material. He is taking the Negative right that his service was never intended to host illegal material, therefore he should not be held responsible for the actions of his users. The United States Department of Justice argue that copyright holders have the right to have their material protected, therefore, Kim Dotcom should be responsible for abiding by the copyright laws of the United States and eliminate the material on MegaUpload that infringes on these Copyright Laws. Since Kim Dotcom had not taken sufficient action to eliminate and mitigate the infringement of Copyrighted material on his site, he is subject to prosecution by the United States Department of Justice. I believe that Kim Dotcom is responsible for the actions that take place on MegaUpload. It is a daunting task to scan billions of files that are present on the file sharing site, but it is necessary to protect the integrity of the content that is hosted on the site. If a site owner turns a blind eye to the content posted on their site, then they should be considered negligent and should face repercussions for permitting illegal actions to take place on their site. It is fair to argue that it is such a daunting task to keep up to date on the content posted on Kim Dotcoms site that it is almost impossible to prevent some copyright material from appearing on the site. It is fair to say that in a general sense a website owner is not subject to judgement based on the actions of the users on said site. However, Kim Dotcom did have the resources and the capabilities to make significant strides toward taking down illegally hosted material on his site. Regarding the next point, Kim Dotcom has also been made aware of the illegal content posted on his site and still took no action towards removing these instances of copyright infringement from his site. Because of this lack of action from Kim Dotcom and his team, and his obvious negligence, Kim Dotcom should be held responsible for the revenue his website stole from content creators around the United States. It is evident that Kim Dotcom is a liar, a cheat, and a criminal. It is true that the website that was created was purely intended to allow users to gain access to content that was too large to attach to an email. However, Kim new that his platform could be used to host massive amounts of data, data that could come from anywhere. MegaUploads users took advantage of this and were able to syphon revenue from content creators by hosting their content for free on the MegaUpload site. Kim Dotcom was fully capable of preventing this from happening. Kim Dotcom was fully capable of removing the content published on his site after learning about the copyright infringement that MegaUpload was lousy with. Kim Dotcom shows no remorse for the victims of this crime and continues to maintain his innocence and deny the necessity for him to take action to protect copyright holders. The United States Department of Justice has an obligation to protect the copyright holders content that is filed with the Government. Because of this, it is obvious that the Government needs to hold these website owners responsible for the content that is hosted on their site. If website owners are made aware of the crimes that are happening on their site, then these website owners should take immediate action to mitigate the crime taking place. If they fail to do so, then the owners of the website should be held responsible in conjunction with the bad actors on the site. To put this situation in laymans terms, it is very similar to a situation of a library owner. The library owner is responsible for daily tasks like checking out books, helping customers, and managing orders. However, they must also be responsible for the people within the library. If someone is too loud then it is their responsibility to remind them to be quiet. If they dont, and they let these people continue to disrupt the peace, which ruins the library for everyone, and then it is no longer working like a library should. In conclusion Kim Dotcom continues to avoid justice and works towards maintaining his innocence while living in New Zealand. It is evident that MegaUpload functionality was abused to host pirated content at the expense of the copyright owners who created the content. This loss of revenue should push the Government to act and make changes that make site owners more responsible for the content published on their site. Hopefully, when these changes occur, they will mitigate the pirating that takes place on the internet, and reward content creators with the money they deserve.

In September of 2012, a New Zealand judge said Kim Dotcom could potentially be sent to the United States of America to stand a trial for a series of criminal charges including copyright infringement, racketeering, wire fraud, and money laundering1 in regards to an online storage locker room otherwise known as Megaupload. At age 41, Kim Dotcom was making a bang for his buck. He opened a file hosting service called Megaupload. This company was financially successful until the United States Department of Justice seized his website and pressed charges against Dotcom for reasons previously stated. Dotcom, in 2012, resided in New Zealand where New Zealand police raided his home and arrested him. In 2017, a New Zealand court ruled that Dotcom, and everyone who was accused in this scandal, could be extradited to the US on fraud charges related to Megaupload. Dotcom denied the wrongdoings that were pressed against him and blamed the US authorities for creating this vendetta against him. This company did more than $100 Million in business which was considered piracy. This website collected money from people primarily through membership fees. Over 150 Million users were subscribed with servers in several countries. Its terms of use prohibited infringement and when notified, the infringing material was taken down. Once Dotcom was arrested for these criminal charges, his website affected the market for movies when viewing a study that showed that online sales and rentals of movies were up 6-10% after shutting down Megaupload and a similar site such as Megavideo. Throughout this scandal, there were positive and negative rights going through Dotcoms thought process. A negative right that heavily outweighs any possible positive right in this situation is money laundering. Dotcom stole money from people supporting his website which makes this a negative right because this is not interfered with and benefits him and his crew with money. A positive right involved was technically offering this service to hundreds of millions of users. These users could upload anything to the web with a click of a button and people who paid for premium accounts were able to upload and download larger files.3 This clearly does not look good for Kim Dotcom and many people will consider him a criminal. There are two positions to look at here. Kim Dotcom a certified criminal, or the US and New Zealand authorities party poopers. The reason why people would consider Dotcom a criminal is because there is evidence. Dotcom committed copyright infringement, racketeering, wire fraud, and money laundering. These all are examples of potential criminal activities. The other position is looking at the US and New Zealand authorities as party poopers. An argument for this could be that the New Zealand Government Communications Security Bureau (GCSB) had spied on Dotcom and none of this information should have been leaked and Dotcom could have still potentially been successful.2 The GCSB was illegally helping the police locate Dotcom and monitor his communications weeks prior to the raid on his house. Three days later after the arrest of Kim Dotcom, the prime minister, John Key apologized for the illegal spying because he thought it was truly unfair. When asked if Dotcom is a hero, a criminal, or in between, my answer would be that he is a criminal. From what I grasped throughout his journey in the making of this website, Megaupload, it seems like he stole a lot of peoples money from essentially just membership fees which totaled to around $100 Million. Never would I consider him a hero, but I could see how an argument of putting him in between would pan out. If I were to fight for Dotcom to be in between a hero and a criminal, I could say that he provided a service for more than one hundred fifty million that nobody else could offer. Other than that, he is just a criminal. Now, regarding the government that is responsible for punishing the individuals, it should be straightforward. They should be sent to jail for any type of money laundering, especially in this case which was over one hundred million dollars. Dotcom was indeed sent to jail but was given a bail price and was ordered to pay $2500 to the GCSB. He had also lost a court bid for damages against the GCSB. There are many instances where scandals related to money laundering happen in the real-life world not relating to any cyber security stuff. A few years ago, in a town very close to mine, my parents would take us swimming at this very nice pool where people all over the surrounding towns could only go. You were only allowed to enter if you had a leisure pass which lasted the whole summer. These leisure passes were purchased months before summer began so it was fast and simple. One year, my parents purchased the leisure pass and the first week of summer, they said they were having issues with the pool filters and they could not let anyone in because the water in the pools were not clean. We waited about a month and they would not answer my parents or my parents friends phone calls. This confused all the leisure pass owners because it was a fair amount of money around $750 for the summer so nobody was comfortable paying this and not being able to attend the pools. In November, parents were receiving calls letting them know that there was a whole money laundering situation and that the person running the business was arrested. The people who called were investigators of the case and said everyone would be refunded in full amount.
