This might be a little different than the Dotcom scandal because the service that was being offered was not even available to the people paying so owner of this business was surrounded by negative rights, otherwise known as money laundering. Kim Dotcom was a smart man, yet risky. The things he did to achieve fame and a successful business were considered sketchy, but well executed at the same time if it was not for the illegal spies. All in all, Kim Dotcom was found to be a criminal and should not be able to justify his actions.

Over the course of the internets lifespan, there have been massive leaps and bounds in improvement. Regarding file space, we may be used to devices being able to hold terabytes of storage, but file storage used to be extremely small by todays standards, starting with only about 5 memory bytes [1]. However, storage has advanced to the point where we have cyberlockers, third party websites that allow people to store files online. While this feature is definitively a very efficient and convenient feature to have, it can be used with ill intent, most notably piracy. In 2005, Kim Schmitz Dotcom founded Megaupload, a cyberlocker that allowed people to store files online and view them. The site operated from Hong Kong and New Zealand. Kim Dotcom made profit from this website through membership fees and advertisements, before it was seized by the U.S. Government, the website had over 180,000 million registered users, had servers in several countries, and did over $100 million in business. However, the website was also plagued by a problem, piracy. The website was used to illegally share movies and other works of art that were protected by copyright. In Megauploads terms of service, it states that copyright infringement is prohibited, and that the website takes down any files that violate copyright laws when notified. It was stated that Kim Dotcom generated about $170 million in profit, as well as causing $500 million in harm to copyright owners. As a result, Kim was arrested in 2010 and Megaupload was seized by the U.S. Government. Afterwards Kim fled to New Zealand and has been fighting against being extradited to the U.S. to face further charges. In 2020, Kims fight is still ongoing. Although he was unsuccessful when bringing the case to New Zealands appeals court, his case has now been brought to the Supreme Court where if he loses, he would be extradited to the U.S. Kim Dotcom himself has said that he does not expect to win [2] and it seems almost inevitable that he will be extradited. In this case, there are two factors we can look at, positive and negative rights. Negative rights are the obligation others must not interfere with someones actions. Positive rights are the right to provide some type of benefit to someone or something. This case has some examples of both. The main negative right involved is Megauploads right to not be interfered with. Megauploads purpose is to share files which is not an issue and deserves not to be interfered with. However, it gets complicated when that file sharing is used to commit a crime, which puts the negative right into question. In contrast, the main positive right in question is the governmental authority to interfere with Megaupload in order to benefit copyright holders. The reason that Megaupload faced so much scrutiny is because their service was used to pirate different copyrighted works of art. As such, it can easily be argued that the government has the positive right to interfere for the benefit of others. Determining whether what happened to Megaupload and Kim Dotcom requires careful thought of each factor. Megauploads terms of service specifically stated that sharing copyrighted material was not allowed and that Megaupload would take it down when notified. As a file sharing service with over 180 million users, it would be next to impossible to take down every single pirated material that gets shared onto their site. If they ban the offender, that offender can just make a new account and repost it under a different name. Megauploads role is just to host and share files and it can be argued that pirated files being hosted on their site is a problem that is beyond their responsibility as they already denounce and forbid it on their website. However, the interesting factor here is that they also state that they will take it down when notified. This clause is very interesting as it provides a lot of flexibility when it comes to them having to deal with people posting pirated files. If they can argue that they were not notified, or if they were not notified at all, then the pirated material would have a free pass to stay on the website. While piracy is still a crime, it was taken a lot more seriously in the past. With Megaupload, the influence they had meant anyone could gain access to copyrighted materials internationally. Its also worth noting that Kim profited from hosting the pirated files. If you take the when notified clause in Megauploads terms of service and the profit they gained from having the pirated content hosted on their website, its a clear cut decision for the government to step in to stop any further piracy and crimes. Kim Dotcom is a controversial figure for sure. Some can regard him as a hero who was unjustly punished, or a villain who profited from copyright infringement. Its hard to come up with a proper title, but the closest would be a criminal. While the file sharing service may not have been made with any ill intent, there was not enough action done by Kim to prevent piracy from being spread on his very own platform. In addition, he also directly profited from this. Although Megaupload did over $100 million worth of business, Kim made over $175 million in criminal proceeds, likely due to the piracy on his platform. He also cost copyright holders collectively about $500 million. Looking at what people have lost compared to what Kim gained from illegal activities on his website, Kim Dotcom can objectively be labeled a criminal. Governments holding people responsible for committing a crime is very easy to do as they clearly broke the law, but what about if someone just facilitates a crime? Its very circumstantial, but the consensus is that a crime is a crime. Even if you dont know that the crime is occurring, indirectly contributing to it can be considered a crime. To fully understand this, we can use an analogy. The scenario is as follows: Youre the owner of a bar. You run it like a normal bar and its quite popular, drawing in a crowd. However, a group of people use your bar to gamble illegally. While you make it clear that gambling is not allowed, you have no clue that its going on until the police show up and apprehend them. You find out that people use some of the money they won through the illegal activities and bought products from you, also making you profit from their activities. While it may not be fair, you did give the criminals a place to conduct their activities, hence facilitating the crime. The government should intervene whenever they believe that a crime is being committed, but they should also view the entire situation at hand when determining if someone facilitated a crime. If the person did not have any knowledge of the crime, it wouldnt be morally correct to convict them, but if they still broke the law whether directly or indirectly, its only fair that consequences are given. Piracy is a very important crime to watch out for. Piracy can severely hurt copyright holders and content creators as they can lose a significant portion of their venue. While Kim Dotcom is still facing charges, piracy has been somewhat normalized. Now, its very easy to pirate videos or games using streaming services or torrents. Kim Dotcom was the first to be apprehended for practically endorsing privacy, and he most likely wont be the last.

People's daily life has been inseparable from the Internet. All walks of life depend on the Internet in various forms, which benefits from the sharing of information. However, when people obtain useful information for themselves, they sometimes touch the field of cybercrime and copyright disputes. In the case of Kim Dotcom, this contradiction is highlighted. MegaUpload, once a famous online disk service provider in the United States, headquartered in Hong Kong However, was forcibly closed by the U.S. Department of justice due to copyright disputes on January 19, 2012. It turned out that the company has generated more than $175 million in criminal proceeds and more than $500 million in damages to copyright owners. However, Kim Dotcom, the company's owner, denied the charges of online piracy and took various measures to avoid being extradited to the United States. He said his website only provides an online storage platform for documents and should not be responsible for what kind of content is saved. According to this belief and leaning the lesson from MegaUpload, Dotcom restarted Mega on January 20, 2013 with some new features. When users share files, in addition to giving sharing links, they are also required to provide secret keys to content recipients in other ways to protect the privacy and security of files. This means that Mega users can upload, store and share pictures, text, music and movies, but these files will be encrypted, and the only decryption key will be kept by the user. Mega could not be exempted from legal liability due to its inability to access its files. In this way, Mega shifted the responsibility of piracy censorship to users who upload content. The U.S. film industry used to believe that the site should be directly responsible for illegal content uploaded by users. Now, this dilemma has been cleverly bypassed, but it also means that the way Mega spreads has been fundamentally changed. In the era of MegaUpload, users could download and open any file with only one website address; now, users must obtain the key provided by the uploader before downloading files, which greatly improves the threshold of file sharing. Mega has attracted a million visitors and half of them to sign up on its first day, and Dotcom was flattered by users' willingness to pay. Their site even experienced an overload. On the question of whether Mega would fall into the same legal dispute, Dotcom said the business was completely different from MegaUpload and even included core code. The site was developed entirely in HTML5, and some of the code is not even recognized by official standards. From a server security point of view, developing a brand-new website also has advantages. Mega does not use any existing technology, turns out that the server will not be cracked at all. From an objective point of view, in the era of MegaUpload, this case involves positive rights of many citizens, such as the right of the author of the original work to seek copyright protection from the law, and the right of MegaUpload members to ask for paid services from the company. Besides, this case has also damaged the negative rights of many citizens, including the copyright held by the author of the original work and the right of MegaUpload members to do whatever they like with their own property. However, in the era of mega, the company's infringement of the original author's copyright does not seem to be eradicated. Users can still accurately locate the pirated content they are interested in through third-party search engines. Although there is so-called password protection, users who make profits by uploading pirated content will definitely disclose their passwords to members through their dedicated channels, and this "convenience" for users is obviously illegal. With the development of information technology, online disks and related functions are becoming more and more popular, which also gives users the opportunity to upload and disseminate infringing and pirated works through online disks. This not only damages the legitimate rights and interests of copyright owners, but also brings litigation risk to the online disk operators. Mega has brought great convenience to people, but at the same time, many people have fallen into the quagmire of copyright infringement. Therefore, in order to confirm the moral status of the founders of online disk companies, and to balance the efforts of the government to investigate the illegal piracy activities of individuals, the first priority is identify the advantages and disadvantages of online disk. Online disk is a professional network storage tool and a benchmark of Internet cloud technology. With the rapid development of cloud computing technology, the cost of network storage has dropped sharply, and the online disk has been constantly updated and improved. Its technology and functions have also been strengthened. From a simple storage tool, it has gradually evolved into an advanced product with information sharing, reading, downloading and other services, providing convenience for the majority of Internet users. Among them, file sharing has become a hot spot in the online disk. Users can share their stored resources to others, and they can also search for the resources they want in the resource group. This function can share videos, e-books, software, within a reasonable range for learning and appreciation. In contrast, the risk of infringement is hidden in the file sharing function. Precious art works usually cost many human and financial resources, and the sharing of unauthorized works seriously infringes the copyright owner's right of information network dissemination. In order to profit from it, the lawbreakers ignore the law and eventually turn this convenient technology into a tool for making pirated and infringing products. After all, in the advocating free environment, users hold the mentality of taking advantage of it, and it is easy to encourage the unhealthy atmosphere of piracy. From this point of view, the contradiction between the interests of the people and the legitimacy of online disks is essentially a dispute over copyright. However, the government must not ignore the convenient and comfortable learning and working environment that online disk brings to many schools and companies. In other words, information sharing is not all immoral. Therefore, Dotcom's moral status should be something between hero and criminal. Besides, for the government, the work of dealing with the disputes between online disk company and the people's interests should be carried out with the copyright as the center. More specifically, the way to deal with the cyber-copyright issues should refer to the user's degree of citation and motivation of the publication. It can be said that there is no perfect solution which satisfy both sides approach to this sort of ambiguity, but at the very least, such guidelines can ensure that the laws could protect the interests of online disk members while maintaining the copyright as much as possible.

Kim Schmitz (also known as Dotcom, Kimble, and Kim Tim Jim Vestor) was the owner of Megaupload, Trendax, Data Protect Limited, Kimvestor Limited, and Monkey Limited . Living in Germany, Dotcom was renowned for fraudulent technological activities and managed to avoid being formally charged several times. But by 1998, he was convicted of, among other charges, 11 counts of computer fraud, 10 counts of data espionage, and an assortment of other charges . Because he was considered to be a minor when the crimes allegedly took place, he received a minor sentence and his unethical activities continued. In the early 2000s, he claimed to have hacked U.S. institutions like Citibank and NASA. In the late 90s, Dotcom had used phone calling card codes he had purchased from American hackers and committed a series of phreaking frauds. In Hong Kong and the Caribbean, Kim set up premium toll chat lines, using a "war dialer" software to dial the numbers stolen. The program logs a telephone number whenever it finds a modem. Later after the program has called every extension, the hacker can review the log for modems and go back and attempt to break into the system to which the modem is connected to gain access to the network . He also claimed to have gotten access to hundreds of US companies' PBX systems and was making profits by selling access codes to these PBX systems for $200 each. Dotcom had gained up to 61,000 in ill-gained revenue . During his life as a hacker, he has moved from Germany to Hong Kong and then to New Zealand. In 2021 the US brought charges of copyright infringement, racketeering, wire fraud, and money laundering against Dotcom and has been trying to have him extradited from New Zealand to the U.S. to face those charges in court. In 2005 Dotcom created Megaupload, a digital storage locker that allowed users to upload pirated PC software onto a platform Dotcom had developed; then Dotcom marketed this as a service to others, inviting them to pay for access to these so-called free (but illegally uploaded) materials. Dotcom enjoyed notable profits until 2012 when the U.S. FBI accused him of wildly violating copyright laws and shut down the site . Dotcom attempted to incorporate his security company Data Protect into the "legit" security world initially backfired by revealing his real identity and enabling it to be linked to his hacker credentials . Dotcom is now facing an extradition trial after being refused bail at an initial hearing in a New Zealand prison. He denies all charges against him strongly. After considering Dotcoms history and allegations I do not believe he is a hero. I believe he is a criminal because he, his company, and colleagues breached copyright infringement on a major scale by hosting illegally created music, film and software files . There is nothing heroic in stealing someone elses work, denying them the profits owed to them for that work, and then making a profit from that theft. Consumers who feel they have a right to such materials for free misunderstand the fact that they are stealing from the artists and creators of these materials. Such theft is illegal and should be punished as established by a countrys federal laws. The negative rights in this case state that Dotcom has the right to act in a way free from other limitations. So theoretically he can create a platform that allows people to upload and download materials that do not belong to them, and he may provide that service. However, the positive rights obligate the government to enact its laws and Dotcom was causing companies and/or designers to lost revenue because of illegally sold copies (because piracy forced the price down), as well as profits lost from pirated copies; copyright infringement is not a liberty companies are allowed to take without facing consequences . So, because he is blatantly violating the law, the government is obligated to take the appropriate, assigned action to punish him (or at least stop his behaviors). The governments (in the US or elsewhere) should hold people responsible for facilitating illegal activity based on the ramifications of their actions and the reason behind it. In this case, Dotcom cost the film and music industry $500 million in losses and for that violation of laws, he deserves to be extradited to face his punishment. These are not unique circumstances for the private security world. For example, when Joaquin El Chapo Guzman, who had escaped from multiple high-security prisons and lived on the run for years, finally got extradited to the United States to face prosecution on narcotics and other charges, justice was finally served . The consequences of El Chapos actions in the Sinaloa Cartel escalated the countrys drug war, which has cost the lives of more than 200,000 people. Extradition and punishment are constructing most countries value and uphold; therefore, seeking appropriate reparation from Dotcom is not only appropriate but necessary ethically. Another example of governments (in the US or elsewhere) holding people responsible for facilitating illegal activity is Napster. Napster was a file-sharing application used to download music from each other's computers . In 1998, someone with the username "Napster" announced in an internet chatroom that he'd been working on a software to fix the errors for downloading music offline. His idea, Napster, allowed people to share their MP3 music files online. After the manufacturing and creation of Napster, the RIAA, The Recording Industry Association of America, was horrified by Napsters breach of copyright and properly took action to sue users and owners . The RIAA argued Napsters software allows users to violate music copyrights, it also calculated that Napster cost the music industry more than $300 million in lost revenue. At the time of the court decision rap artist Wyclef Jeans comments are reminiscent of the Dotcom situation. Jean said that, When an artist gives permission to [take] their music, its cool, [b]ut if you just take itand you do what you want with it and the artist doesnt have control, I think thats foul. Perhaps some see Dotcoms actions as a sort of Robin Hood behavior, where he takes materials like videos or music or software and provides them to people for free. However, this is not something to celebrate. It is no different than stealing someones code without paying them for it or taking someones coveted recipe and using it for ones own profit without permission. Such behaviors are theft. It is not Dotcoms jurisdiction to decide that such materials should be available for free. Thats simply not how the capitalistic market works, and its definitely not how the law works. The question of whether or not governments should hold violators and facilitators of illegal activities accountable seems to be moot, in my opinion, or at least very obvious. It is not only the responsibility of governments to act to halt people who violate laws, but it is arguably the entire purpose of a government. A government (in the US, the combination of the 3 branches of government working together) is supposed to create laws that keep its people safe and allow society to work effectively. In the US we have laws regulating everything from speech to traffic flow to theft to manslaughter. So why would the governments right to prosecute someone who breaks those laws of ownership even be a question? Would it be nice to have everything we want for free? Sure. But thats not the way American capitalism and economic policies are designed, and Mr. Dotcom does not get to make his own rules.

Abstract Copyright infringement affects the technology and entertainment industry in many ways. In the case where Megaupload is the main controversy, it is evident that copyright infringement affects the founder and governments involved. There will be an emphasis throughout the essay on how the founder was affected by this case. There will be suggestions on what things should be done in future cases of this matter. In addition, an example presented will provide an insight into how other industries can be affected by copyright infringement.

The Megaupload takedown and following legal battle has been a major battle for copyright protection with varying views on both sides. There are different opinions as to how the rights of each party have been infringed upon and by whom. There are those who claim that Megaupload is guilty of massive amounts of copyright infringement and there are those who claim that Megaupload was the victim of government censorship and pressure by Hollywood to take down a competitor in exchange for their weighty support in the government. The legal proceedings between the government of the United States and Kim Dotcom have been continuing for over seven years since his arrest in 2012. Since his initial arrest Kim has gone through a few different business ventures including creating a political party in New Zealand and even recording a music album. After his move to New Zealand Kim Dotcom has continued to fight against extradition to the United States of America. The most recent ruling on his case was given on July 5, 2018. The New Zealand Court of Appeals upheld a decision by a lower court stating that he could be extradited for his crimes. Kims defense lawyers appealed immediately to the Supreme Court of New Zealand and as of October 2020 the Supreme court of New Zealand has yet to make a judgement. Kim Dotcom also distanced himself from the website mega.nz and has undergone quite a few different business ventures and changes. Kim founded the Internet Party in New Zealand in March 2014 and worked to attempt to get seats on New Zealands parliament. This attempt ultimately failed, and Dotcom stepped down from his leading role in the political party. The Internet Party was deregistered as a political party in 2018 due to it failing to maintain the minimum number of members. The website Mega.nz is still a functioning cloud storage website, however it functions completely without any influence from Kim Dotcom. Kim has even publicly stated that Mega was taken over by a hostile Chinese investor whos shares were then seized by the New Zealand government. Kim said that he would not advise trusting the security of information stored on Mega. There are many different rights involved in the case against Kim Dotcom. The United States is claiming many cases of copyright infringement, which directly violates the negative rights of the copyright holders. This claim has a strong basis due to the evidence gathered by the United States. When the domain Megaupload.com was seized by the United States government and operations shut down Movie Kim Dotcom has claimed that his positive right as a permanent resident of New Zealand to not be spied on was violated by the New Zealand Government Communications Security Bureau, who monitored his communications prior to the police raid on his residence. It is worth considering that Kim Dotcoms negative rights could also be viewed as having been violated if his website Megaupload should have been protected under the Digital Millennium Copyright Act. If he should have been protected and the website was taken down this could be viewed as censorship. We should also note that not everything on the website constituted copyright infringement, yet the website in its entirety was shut down. There are many different arguments for which side is correct in this situation. Kim Dotcom has made many such arguments against the United States throughout the many years of his legal battles. Kim has shared how his sites were in practice not significantly different than websites such as Youtube and therefor should be protected by the Digital Millennium Copyright Act under the Safe Harbor provision. This provision states that online service providers are immune to claims of copyright infringement if they promptly remove or block access to infringing materials after being given notice of the infringement. Kim has made the claim that Megaupload complied with all such requests as soon as possible after they received the notifications from copyright holders. If Megaupload was in compliance with the DMCA as the claim has been made than Kims negative rights to conduct business without interference could have been infringed upon. Kims rights to privacy as given by the laws of New Zealand could also have been violated during the raid on his home in which the New Zealand police arrested Kim and his co-workers. Up until 2017, in New Zealand a permanent resident or citizen may not be spied upon by government agencies. Therefor the spying on Kim Dotcom could have constituted a breach of his privacy and thus infringed on his negative rights to be left alone. The GCSB admitted to this misstep and the government of New Zealand issued an apology for the incident. The rights of the copyright holders are the most obvious to see in my opinion. Megaupload was well known for being a place one could go to find pirated movies online and though they may claim they actively followed up on taking down reported infringing content, it was ineffective. The US government claims that the report abuse tool that was used by Megaupload was not actually a functioning DMCA compliance tool.[1] The government ruled that it was not protected under the DMCA for that reason and the fact that the website was making money on the materials. This is also supported by the study from Carnegie Mellons Initiative for Digital Entertainment Analytics that showed an increase in legal movie downloads of six to ten percent.[2] The movie studios that suffered the most from Megauploads illegal file sharing likely suffered major monetary losses directly correlating with people instead getting the movie from Megaupload. In the charges against Megaupload the justice department claimed damages well in excess of $500 million 3. Instead of the cost of the movie going to the benefit of those who actively used their resources to produce the work, the money was given to Megaupload who had no rights to the works that they were gaining money on. There have also been claims made that Megaupload and Kim Dotcom are just victims of the U.S. government trying to mollify the motion picture industry in exchange for campaign contributions and political support [3]. These claims are based around Kims own claims that Megaupload was a similar hosting platform to Youtube and that it did properly monitor in accordance to the DMCA. In Kims own claims the United States is attempting to prosecute based on what he calls secondary copyright infringement, which is to say Megaupload is being prosecuted based on the copyright infringement of its users. Megaupload itself did not actually post and provide any of the content on its website. It was simply the hosting platform. He further claims that secondary copyright infringement is not a crime in the United States. In comparison, if a company was known to be selling stolen bicycles even after they were reported as stolen. The company could be charged with dealing in stolen property. Regardless of whether that company physically stole the bikes themselves, they are responsible for selling them and making a profit from stolen goods and then, even after finding out they are stolen, continuing to deal in the bikes. Claiming that they did not break any laws because someone else stole the bikes would simply be ludicrous. While many of these arguments do hold merit and there is clearly rights that were violated on both sides I am of the opinion that sites such as megaupload.com which do not offer sufficient protections for copyrighted work should therefor be prosecuted and held responsible for copyright infringement. Governments across the globe have a duty to protect their citizens and their citizens properties, whether intellectual or otherwise.

Megaupload was a popular file sharing website founded in 2005. Before then, the most popular way to share files was to email them to each other, but the file size was limited. People were using the site to upload and share copyrighted material. At one point it was the 13th most popular website on the internet. The owners of the website did not put enough effort into taking down the copyrighted material, so it was shut down in 2012. The owner and creator of the site, Kim Dotcom, was arrested in New Zealand. Since then Dotcom has posted bail and still lives in New Zealand. The United States has filed charges against Dotcom and can be extradited if the New Zealand court allows. The U.S. claims that the website has costed copyright holders an estimate of $500 million in lost revenue [1]. Kim Dotcom has helped start a new company called Mega Ltd. with other people who also worked at Megaupload. It offers a similar service of cloud storage but is also encrypted and anonymous. Although Dotcom helped launch the company, Dotcom is not listed as a shareholder nor a director, but on the Mega website he is called principal strategist [2]. Since being arrested, Dotcom has been staying in his nice mansion in New Zealand. The New Zealand government has also illegally spied on Dotcom which led to the Prime Minister apologizing [2]. The positive rights of using the website are the rights to upload and download. Uploading and downloading from the website lets users store files and information. Another positive right would be the right to share. When someone uploads a file to the website, they have the right to share the link or the file with another person. These could be negative rights for the company since they have to host the files and keep the website running. They are also negative rights to companies since these files may contain copyrighted material. The copyright holders may be losing out on a lot of money if users are downloading it for free rather than buying it. This may be a positive right for the website. If more people come to Megaupload, the website will generate more ad revenue and will make more money. I am against file sharing of copyrighted material and I agree with what happened. Megaupload should have been stricter with what files could be uploaded to the site. The site was particularly more attractive to software pirates because they did not check the files as much. I think the company knew what was going on and was not doing much to remove the copyrighted material. I do believe the sharing of information is important and should be free, but piracy is not ok. The copyright holders who made the content should be at least getting a cut from what the website is making. Megaupload was making money by hosting copyrighted material but not sharing any of the profits with the respective holders. When Megaupload got a copyright claim, they did not delete the file itself, but just deleted the link to download the file. When someone uploaded a file that has already been previously uploaded, they do not make a copy but instead just create a new link pointing to the same file [3]. This can save storage and also reduce the time on when files are uploaded. The problem was that multiple links could have led to the same file, which may have not also been taken down. If Megaupload actually deleted the files when they got a copyright claim and took it more seriously, they might still have the site up. I do not think Kim Dotcom is a hero nor a criminal, but instead something in between. He was the one that created the site that stored the copyrighted material, but he was not the one directly uploading the files. Although he had no direct contact with the files at all, he should have been enforcing the law on his site and removing anything that infringed on copyright. I think his work has certainly influenced others, which may not be a good thing, but it is definitely noteworthy in internet history. In circumstances like this, I think the government should be minimally invasive. I think the companies should file copyright claims or copyright takedowns first. It would be easier and may be more efficient for companies to contact the website owner before getting the government involved. I think the government should only get involved if the website is a repeat offender and will not listen to the respected copyright holders. There are hundreds if not thousands of sites on the internet that illegally share copyrighted material. It would take up so much of the governments time to take down each and every one. If there is a company that is knowingly and willfully sharing copyrighted material that is not theirs and without the permission of the copyright holders, they deserved to be punished. As for punishment when they arrest someone, I would say it depends on the damage it caused to copyright holders. There is still precedent to be set when dealing with illegal file sharing in terms of punishment. A non-cyber analogy to this would be physical bootlegs of media. A bootleg can be defined as a non-official copy of something. This can be copies of CDs, DVDs, Vinyl records, and even apparel. Often when going to a concert, you may see people on the side of the street trying to sell CDs or T-shirts of the artist playing. They obviously are not official, but they may give off a similar quality to the original. Although the bootlegs may be cheaper than the official version, you will probably get a lower quality item and you will not be supporting the artist who created the content. Although I do not support bootlegging, some forms may be worse than others. Sometimes an artist does not release a form of music on a certain platform that people want it on. It has always been legal to burn music to a DVD if you buy it digitally. You can easily do that at home, but what if the consumer wants it on vinyl? Now that vinyl records are becoming more popular again, you can find records on vinyl that have never officially released on that format. You can find these records typically on sites like eBay and Amazon, but also in record stores. Buyers may think these are official when they are not since there is no other version. Bootlegging goes farther than digital entertainment. There are websites that use and sell copyrighted work without the owners permission. One example is the apparel site Redbubble. Users can upload an image, and the company will print it on an article of clothing. If you type the name of any major company into their search bar, you will see their logo, likely not uploaded or used with their permission. The good thing is that at the bottom of the page, you can report the content and it will likely be removed if it infringed on copyright.

The legality of file sharing on the internet has been in question almost since its inception. Whether it be large song sharing spaces like Napster or the now infamous Megaupload, this sharing of music, video, and other files has been fought by officials and copyright owners vehemently. Despite this, however, many still claim that the operation and utilization of these websites is well within their rights as consumers, and even though file sharing(dubbed piracy) of intellectual property is illegal, the ethical implications, as well as the complicated nature of enforcing such a law on something as open as the internet, means that the debate about piracy continues to this day. Megaupload, founded in 2005 by Kim Dotcom, has been described as one of the internets largest file-sharing sites. Before discussing the eccentric nature of its founder, it should be said that Megaupload was an online file sharing website where anyone could upload files of (nearly) any size to a server, where the files could then be downloaded and shared freely. While Megauploads services seems like a fine idea on paper, internet piracy was seemingly allowed to run rampant on the service, and movies, music, tv shows, and other intellectual property were shared without the permission of the copyright owner. The flagrant publication of copyrighted material eventually caught the eye of the United States government, who took legal action against the company, claiming it was facilitating the distribution of copyright infringing materials. Ultimately, the site was shut down because of these legal actions, ending its reign as one of the most visited websites on the internet. However, it did not experience a peaceful ending. Government officials executed raids on hundreds of Megaupload servers, as well as on founder Kim Dotcoms New Zealand home, taking him into custody. As of 2018, Kim Dotcom was still fighting his extradition to the United States, and continuously appeals rulings in a last ditch attempt to avoid it. Ethically, who is in the right here? Is it the fault of Kim Dotcom that people used his file sharing website, which had anti-piracy tools (albeit used quite minimally), to spread illegal and copyright infringing material? One might argue that Kim Dotcom is well within his rights to pursue and shape his organization however he wants, and barely moderating his website falls within his rights. However, Kim Dotcom does not have the right to pull money away from copyright and intellectual property owners, so the flipside of this argument is that his lack of anti-piracy enforcement actively hurts the livelihood of others. This stance is obviously the position that the United States government has taken, and while seemingly harsh at face value, it seems to be the only position they could have taken, lest they allow what essentially boils down to obscene and obvious illegal distribution to continue. It is a hard question to posit, as both sides are not without merit, but in this case, I believe the US government did the right thing in defending the intellectual property of its creators. As stated, I believe that if allowed to run wild indefinitely, it would have set a dangerous precedent which would encourage more and more people to stop purchasing access to shows and movies, and instead pirate them for free. I also think that just destroying Megaupload was a rash and poorly thought out move, as unlike websites solely dedicated to illegally sharing copyrighted files, Megaupload also dealt in legitimate data storage and file sharing. At the end of the day, the U.S had to protect its copyright enforcement laws, so they made an example out of Megaupload and its founder, but the unrefined and forceful way they did it directly harms users who simply needed a space to store and share perfectly legal and innocuous data. The question is Dotcom a hero has a simple answer : no, not by any stretch. He is a hacker of questionable morality who has partaken in several shady enterprises in his lifetime, with Megaupload simply being his most famous and successful endeavor. However, the question is he a criminal is harder to answer, specifically in the context of Megaupload and its services. Weve already discusses the argument that Dotcom shouldnt be held responsible for the content his users share and store on the platform, copyright infringing or not. The intent of the service does matter, however, and based on Dotcoms history as a hacker and public participation in major data breaches, it is understandable why one might see him as suspect when he operates a file sharing website known for piracy. I think it would be sufficient to label him as something else entirely, since, in spite of his charges and all around shady behavior, I do align with the idea that he shouldnt be held responsible for the content his users store on his servers, The extent that governments should hold people responsible for facilitating illegal activity is a question that has no concrete answer. Illegal file sharing happens all the time, and while Im not one of the people uploading tons of content illegally, Ive definitely downloaded a song and shared it with my friends before. Free and open file sharing is a large part of internet culture, regardless of the explicit legality of it, and likely will be a part of it for a long time. This makes it extremely difficult to enforce any anti-piracy laws on people who are using the uploaded content, as penalizing millions of people is a daunting and unrealistic task, especially when the internet grants so much anonymity. The distributors and site hosts, as weve seen, are a different story. I (hypocritically, I suppose) support the notion that the U.S. should go after those who distribute copyrighted materials illicitly, as it protects the revenue stream of the artists that produce the work in the first place. However, Id be remiss if I didnt once again mention that there are some serious benefits for internet users to have an open file sharing website. For example, even though I would never use such a service, I know many college students that saved near thousands of dollars by pirating textbooks for their classes on the internet. Essentially, a case by case system of dealing with piracy is needed, despite the current legislative effort to make a blanket rule. If somebody uploads all 5 seasons of Breaking Bad to the internet, the government should probably step in and protect the creators intellectual property by shutting down the distributor. But if somebody uploads clips of a 40-year-old TV show that doesnt get produce on tape or disc anymore, its probably fine to leave up, as the accessibility to purchase the product is severely limited. To conclude and hopefully drive my point home, think about if somebody got (accidentally) shot while at a gun range. Who is at fault? The person who shot the victim, or the gun range, for not properly enforcing gun safety rules? Both arguments are valid, and the shooter is obviously at fault, but the guilt of the shooting range is quite ambiguous, as it is in online piracy cases. A clear answer will likely never be found, and debates will continue to be had, even after firm legislation is passed.

In todays world new technologies have changed the way we think about our world and view copyright violation issues in general. Copyright violation is an issue that must be addressed very seriously since it is important to make sure that whenever a new product is invented it is not subject to any sort of violation, that can result in the violation of the integrity of that product . Whether, it is poem, a book, a novel, a software related product its original form must be preserved and the original owner of that product must be offered a patent so that he feels his product his secure . We must also understand the type of copyright violations being committed and must know what policies must be established to protect the integrity of that product and the role the government has to play in solving such problems . A German Entrepreneur Kim Dotcom business Megaupload was shut down by the US government because it illegally contributed to copyright infringement.(Barrie) The police in New Zealand arrested him and his employees.(Barrie) Kim earned more than 175 million dollars in copyright violations and has caused more than 500 million dollars harm to copyright owners.(Barrie) In 2010, Kim went to New Zealand where several attempts are being made to send him back to the United States.(Barrie) Kim recently suffered from an another financial loss after PayPal stopped processing payments for his cloud storage site MEGA.(Barrie) According to a report, MEGA states that the business is not legitimate, which led VISA and Mastercard to put pressure on PayPal to block MEGA.(Barrie) He has been asked by the high court in New Zealand to release some of his 12 million in assets so that he can pay his rent, legal fees , and grocery bills.(Barrie). He claims that he is broke, blaming his financial problems on a $10 million bill that he cannot pay. (Barrie)He had also to deal with the death of one his swans that lived on his luxury mansion(Barrie). His swan was found murdered in his garden (Barrie). Furthermore, his wife Mona Dotcom has run away with a 17-year old boy he hired to play video games with his family(Barrie). There are some negative and positive rights associated with his business. Negative rights are the rights to act without any sort of interference.(Baase) These rights include the right to life, the right to be free from assault, the right to life, liberty, and pursuit of happiness, freedom and speech and religion, the right to work , and the right to have free access to the internet.(Baase)Furthermore, positive rights impose an obligation or a duty for some people to provide certain things to others.(Baase)Some examples of positive rights include that it must be the duty of the government to provide jobs for its people.(Baase) Furthermore, some people must pay for food and medical care for those who cannot pay.(Baase)Another example, would be of providing free access to the internet in the form of aid to people living in poorer countries.(Baase). There are some positive and negative rights associated with Dotcoms actions. The negative rights associated with his actions include him earning 175 million dollars in copyright violations and causing more than 500 million dollars harm to copyright owners, which is the right to work. Furthermore, his going to New Zealand when attempts were made to send him back to the United States is the right to be free from assault. However, there are also some positive rights associated with his actions as well . For example, when asked by the court to him to release some 12 million in assets, he claimed that he was broke which meant that he fulfilled his responsibility of providing information to the court when needed. Furthermore, another positive right associated with his action would include him dealing with the death of a swan that was murdered in his garden. I believe Dotcom is a villain judging by some of his actions and he is also considered a hero in many ways. For example, his copyright violations would be considered a criminal behavior , however, many of his actions can also be considered heroic like he hired a 17 year old programmer to play video games with his family and since he provided information to the court when needed. The government should take necessary steps to hold people responsible for facilitating illegal activity. The severity of the punishment depends upon the nature of the illegal activity. For example, if a person committed an illegal activity that affects the freedom of expression, or is hurtful of ones personal beliefs than the government should fine him for some actions or should imprison him for a temporary period of time. Furthermore, if someone commits a very heinous crime like murder, then should face death penalty or life imprisonment. However, if someone commits a crime on an international level like for example if a person commits a crime in one country and flees to another country , the government of the country that he has fled to must be responsible for deporting him to the country he originally did departure from.In the case of an illegal activity committed online such as hacking ones account or committing financial fraud , no government must be responsible but it is the responsibility of the corporation to hold the person responsible for committing such a crime. For example, if Facebook notes that an individual has hacked someones account then that individuals account must be blocked and that particular individual must be barred from making a new account again. Therefore, it depends upon the situation and the nature of the crime. Some examples of non-cyber copyright violations would include the copyright infringement of a novel, a poem, a photograph, a painting, a lyrics to a song, a sound recording or a movie. I believe copywrite infringement is very a important issue and the government has a major role to play to solve this problem.

Abstract Megaupload is an online upload and web storage site, people need to recharge their membership to use the site, this is a huge amount of illegal income. Megaupload operated from Hong Kong and New Zealand, with servers in several countries, and had 180 million registered users. This website violates the copyright of the film, thus causing great loss to the copyright owners. Federal prosecutors have accused it of costing copyright holders more than $500m (320m) in lost revenue. (BBC News, 2012) Key words: illegal income, copyright, film Introduction Megaupload used to be a very popular website with a lot of users using it. The reason why the site has so many users is that it satisfies the demand of many people to watch movies online. It combines many functions, making it easy for users to find what they want to see and saving money. But in doing so, it infringes on the film's copyright and damages the studios. Users could upload movies, music and other content to the site and share with others, a practice the U.S. considers copyright infringement. (Colin, 2016)

Many people around the world rely on file sharing and hosting services. Sites like Google Drive allow people to create, upload, download, and share files, including formatted text documents and spreadsheets. Google Drive and similar sites allow their users to back up their files, access them in one convenient place, and easily share them with others. While Youtube, does not generally allow videos to be directly downloaded from the site, the video sharing platform is a popular source of entertainment and information for millions, if not billions, of people. Many social media sites, like Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram, also implement video sharing. Soundcloud is an option for sharing and storing audio files. Amazon, Dropbox, and many others offer cloud-based file storage. Until 2012, Megaupload, founded by hacker and entrepreneur Kim Schmitz Dotcom, stood among the aforementioned names. In 2012, Kim Dotcom and several of his associates were indicted on federal charges of copyright infringement, money laundering, wire fraud, and racketeering [1]. It is alleged that they knowingly hosted copyrighted material on servers located in Ashburn in the Eastern District of Virginia, and that they failed to act in response to claims from copyright holders [1, para. 26, 52-57]. In addition, they allegedly mischaracterized their Abuse Tool to copyright holders. While Dotcom and his associates claimed that the Abuse Tool gave rights holders direct access to Megauploads files for the purpose of deletion, the tool only deleted links to the content. The actual files were left intact. When a file was uploaded, its MD5 hash was calculated and compared against the hashes of other files on the site. If an identical file existed, a duplicate file was not created. Instead, only a new link pointing to the same file was created. The Abuse Tool only deleted links that were provided by users of the tool. Thus, if copyright holders were not aware of all links to a given file, the file would remain available and any links not submitted to the Abuse Tool would remain viable. In effect, infringing material was able to remain online despite the efforts of rights holders to claim their content [1, para. 22-24]. The collusion between Kim Dotcom and his associates to commit the aforementioned acts in a coordinated fashion allegedly constitute a criminal enterprise under federal law. This is the basis of the racketeering charge [1, pp. 22-25]. Following the indictment, New Zealand police, acting on a request by the United States government, raided Kim Dotcoms home and arrested him and several of his associates. Since then, they have been embroiled in legal battles [2]. The United States has been seeking extradition. Dotcom and his associates have been fighting the extradition process, which has taken years. The extradition battle is still ongoing [3]. In fact, it could take many more years. The decision is currently up to the Supreme Court of New Zealand. If they rule against Dotcom and his associates, the extraditions need to be approved by the Justice Minister, and his approval could then be appealed, continuing the legal battle further [4]. In addition to his legal battles, Dotcom has made more than one attempt to continue his business. Shortly after his arrest and the shutdown of Megaupload, he was already planning to start another file sharing site called Mega. He claimed that Mega allowed him to avoid the liability that he faced with Megaupload. The former was planned to encrypt files when they were uploaded, and the keys were not to be shared with executives or employees of the company, thus absolving them of responsibility for user-uploaded content [5]. After stepping away from Mega, Dotcom began work on a new file sharing project called K.im, which is currently under development [3]. Dotcom and his business were opposed by many media companies, who claimed that he violated and facilitated others in violating their copyrights. Indeed, producers of intellectual property have a right to exclusively distribute their property. This is a negative right. In other words, the copyright owners have a right to be free of the attempts of others to copy and distribute their intellectual property. The copyright holders also have a right to seek enforcement action against those who infringe upon their copyright. This is a positive right; it is a right to the assistance of the justice system to take action against copyright offenders. Arguably, the copyright holders have not only a right, but a duty to protect their copyright. A law that is not enforced is de facto null and void. Thus, legal protections of intellectual property are meaningless if they are not enforced. Under safe harbor provisions, Kim Dotcom, his associates, and his business have a right to be free from enforcement action resulting from files uploaded by users of Megaupload (a negative right). However, according to a summary of evidence, Dotcom and his associates were involved in criminal activity. Email and Skype chat logs implicate them in a number of crimes and shady dealings. They ignored subpoenas from Indian police. They ignored takedown requests from the Asociacin Protectora de Cine y Msica (APCM), the Mexican analogue to the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA). When one of the conspirators deleted links at the APCMs request, another conspirator persuaded him to reinstate the links. The two then discussed ignoring takedown requests from Mexico and undeleting links from Mexico. They discussed blaming their actions on a glitch if they were caught. They also discussed ignoring enforcement action from VN (presumably Vietnam). Dotcom instructed his associates to reinstate links from non first world countries and to only delete links from the United States, France, Germany, United Kingdom, and Spain [6, para. 133]. They also discuss the use of third party forums for sharing Megaupload links. They discuss profiting from the sites, and they admit knowledge that they are sharing copyrighted material, and they even seem to endorse such activity [6, para 130]. According to their emails, the Megaupload team intentionally copied videos from Youtube and uploaded them to Megaupload. At one point, they claimed to have copied thirty percent of Youtubes videos [6, para. 28]. According to analysis of the websites code, videos were copied from Youtube, then uploaded to Megaupload, where they were tied to a random account and assigned a fake view-count [6, para 29]. Furthermore, a web designer working for Megaupload was instructed to alter the Top 100 list. The web designer was instructed to exclude copyrighted materials from the list, to copy files from other sites, to make fake Megaupload accounts, and to upload the copied files to the fake accounts [6, para 30]. There is much more evidence in the 191 page summary, but the preceding paragraph should suffice to demonstrate that Kim Dotcom and his associates were not acting in furtherance of legitimate business interests. They were acting in a criminal manner. They intentionally infringed the copyrights of numerous individuals and organizations to enrich themselves, and they should be held accountable for their actions. Even though their company was based in Hong Kong and New Zealand, some of the copyrighted data was hosted in the United States, which means it falls under the jurisdiction of the United States and is subject to the laws thereof. Thus, it is reasonable for the United States to request extradition or other legal remedy from New Zealand.

When it comes to sharing digital media, the lines for appropriate use can be unclear: a cyber-environment which promotes the creation and spread of intellectual property must protect the rights of the creator, but also allow freedoms for the audience. If these boundaries are violated, it can be even more difficult to discern the party at fault. As in the case of Megaupload.com (company, site) and founder Kim Dotcom Schmitz, one does not need to be directly involved in copyright infringement to indirectly cause significant damage to the copyright holders. All persons involved in creation or use of digital content must apply ethics to each interaction with creative content to ensure rights are protected for all parties. In the years since the Megaupload takedown in 2012 [1], Dotcom has done all but remain out of the spotlight. He remains in New Zealand as the order for extradition is still open, and entertainment industries are waiting on his return to the U.S. to press charges of copyright infringement against Megaupload [1]. In 2013, Dotcom launched an encrypted sharing service Mega, similar to his previous site, and it has grown to 195 million users who clamor for the services end-to-end encryption [2]. Mega has been quietly growing towards the likes of Dropbox or Apple iCloud, and has a promising future without Dotcom [2]; when he and his wife separated in 2015, he lost nearly all shares in his company [1]. Despite being estranged from his empire, Dotcom maintains his controversy in the tech industry amongst other stages [2], including staunch activism for complete Internet freedom. Ethical considerations play an essential role in this case, and the negative and positive rights of all sides must be considered. The negative right of the pirating users is the crime is easy to get away with; copyright infringement is extremely prevalent, whether intentional or not. The negative right of Dotcom to maintain Megaupload, aware of the infringement activity, is protected by the Freedom of Speech, modified for modern applications to technology. Dotcom has the right to host a cyberlocker website, and the U.S. Governments seizure of the Megaupload domain [3] in efforts to suppress copyright infringement encroaches his negative right to have a website which does not intrinsically violate any laws. In a third view of the copyright holders, the negative right is to protect their materials, or police how their media can be used. The positive rights of the pirating users are to make content available to many people and to remove economic barriers to media maintained by copyright holders and the entertainment industry. The positive right of Dotcom is to host a sharing site where users can share content, including content which infringes copyrights. The positive right of the copyright holders is to allow their content to be shared on these sites, making content available to more people, and possibly gaining influence from the exposure. All these rights, positive and negative, give insight into which side must take the responsibility. Although many circumstances can be debated, it is apparent that Megaupload has enabled copyright infringement, and is at fault. Throughout [3], there are many assertions which can be examined in the dispute of Dotcoms fate. For example, it states, Megauploaddid more than $100 million in business (e.g., from membership fees) [3]. One could say that if the website made the majority of its profit on customer subscriptions as opposed to the copyright infringement committed on its site, then Megaupload was not directly profiting from the pirating and should not be placed at fault. Further in [3], it is stated that U.S. authorities believe Megaupload to have generated $175M in criminal proceeds and caused more than $500M in harm to copyright owners. A company worth over $100M is a substantially large entity, and with size comes capability. It can be argued that, given its extent, Megaupload deserves a scrutinous judgement; generally, the larger a business is, the more difficult it becomes to allow certain behaviors. The statements in [3] also allows discourse of whether Safe Harbor sanctions could be applied to the copyright violations on Megaupload. Safe Harbor laws excuse a violative behavior if there are specific circumstances, commonly referred to as the good faith effort [4]. In one statement, the company defended itself against piracy committed by users, claiming its terms of use prohibited copyright infringement [3]. In favor of Megaupload, as a cyberlocker, the company could not necessarily control what users upload; instead, they placed a legal agreement, describing this condition, on those who wish to use the site and its services. Alternatively, the reliance upon a legal clause for the control of copyright violations, by a business at considerable risk for piracy, could be viewed as nave; perhaps Megaupload could have taken active measures to prevent pirated content from being uploaded on its site in addition to its terms of use. Another statement from Megaupload claimed the company took down infringing material when notified to do so [3]. If this assertion is true, then Safe Harbor sanctions could be applied in the companys favor; if Megaupload forbade piracy in its terms and removed any known violations with due diligence, the company may be regarded as acting in good faith. The phrase, notified to do so, raises doubts about how Megaupload is received such notifications. It seems unlikely for users to be the whistleblowers if piracy was widespread, giving an indication that the company not have made enough effort to closely follow this policy. Further damning evidence states a study found online sales and rentals of movies were 6-10% higher [3] after Megaupload and a similar domain were confiscated by the U.S. government. When this is considered with the aforementioned $500M+ estimated in damages to copyright owners, the large impact of piracy committed on Megaupload is obvious, and the site should be found guilty for enabling copyright infringement. Although there are no straightforward answers in a trial such as this one, I believe that with respect to Megaupload, Dotcom should mostly be considered a criminal. While it is the users responsibility to use the Internet with due diligence to copyrights and applicable laws, it is equally the companys responsibility to prevent and correct such violations as the web host. While there are sanctions such as Safe Harbor which may protect a company from the violations of its users, it is still an ethical duty for the company to facilitate legal connections and data sharing. It is worth being noted, however, that Dotcom brought attention to issues like freedom of speech on the Internet, an important contribution to a hostile topic. To maintain freedoms on the Internet, it is imperative for governments to exercise caution when taking legal action against digital crime. With enough doubt of good faith, criminal activity should be addressed. In the case of businesses, determining who is held responsible poses a problem. Additionally, despite the activity on the site, unless in extreme cases, the removal of an outlet of free speech violates protected rights. Perhaps, in the case of Megaupload, the U.S. government could have forced Dotcom to sell company shares or use profits from the business to pay a fine benefitting those affected by the piracy, or threaten closer monitoring of content upload. An interesting infringement example unrelated to cyber media is the case of Vanilla Ice v. David Bowie/Freddie Mercury (Queen), in which Vanilla Ice sampled the collaborated song Under Pressure on his new song, Ice Ice Baby, without crediting Bowie or Queen [5]. The case ended with Vanilla Ice paying a settlement to both parties and giving credit on his track [5]. Another example of infringement is the case of Isaac Newton v. Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, where the latter began publishing papers on his discovery of Calculus in the late 17th century, while the former published paper in the early 18th century claiming his stakes to the discovery [6]. Ultimately, it was decided that both had individually discovered Calculus at the same time, and now commonly share the credit [6]. The establishment of intellectual material over digital interfaces causes new challenges when considering the creators rights to the property and how others may use the material without interfering with those rights. As seen in the case of Megaupload, enabling theft of copyrighted property is as offensive as piracy itself, despite the distance from direct engagement. As technology rapidly advances, it may be difficult to discern proper credit for creative media in some instances. It is the responsibility and ethical duty for the programmer, business owner, government agency, and Internet user to treat copyrighted materials with respect, and think critically when interacting with digital freedoms.

Megaupload is a well-known online network hard disk service provider. The software can upload large files up to 1GB, save for three months. It has an extremely wide range of users worldwide. Megaupload was founded in 2005. The number of registered users of the site has exceeded 150 million, while the number of daily visitors reached 50 million. Megaupload was once the 13th most visited website on the Internet (Danaher and Smith, 2014). However, due to the spread of a large number of piracy on Megaupload, on January 19, 2012, the US Department of Justice and the Federal Bureau of Investigation shut down Megaupload.com, the world-renowned sharing website. The founder also went to jail because of the incident. The indictment argues that Megaupload differs from other file storage business activities in the way it operates (Danaher and Smith, 2014). The indictment believes that the following design elements in its operating mode are evidence of its criminal intent and risk. Because most users do not have significant private storage capabilities on this website. The more downloaded files will be kept. At the same time, the paid users of the software account for only a small percentage, and the commercial benefits of the software largely depend on advertising. And the website guides users to locate infringing content on the site, share infringing content with others, and even part of the content involves illegal content such as child pornography. Accounts that commit infringements on the site will not be blocked, and the site just uses incentive programs to encourage users to upload more popular files. Even in the court documents, Megaupload is suspected of money laundering. In 2013, the founder was released from prison and Kim Dotcom has created a new site Mega. Official service to the outside world on January 19, 2013. The new platform built by Dotcom this time has made some rectifications compared to MegaUpload, especially in terms of data. Once the website was released, a large number of old users registered and uploaded users. According to reports, the Mega website has received more than 150 copyright infringement warnings in a short period of time. In addition, a third-party search engine was also blocked 24 hours after the release. . Since it was once banned due to piracy issues, Mega is currently very cautious on this issue. Last week, Mega has received more than 150 infringement warnings from copyright owners, but no copyright owners have filed a lawsuit . I think in this incident, the founder Kim was essentially a criminal. Mega has different functions for different subjects. Kim claims to have established a website from the perspective of content creators in order to allow creators themselves to obtain huge profits. As the Internet makes the marginal cost of content and information dissemination close to zero, huge demand has given birth to many unicorns with high market value, such as Netflix and Spotify (Peukert et al, 2017). Although these service-oriented platforms provide users and creators with higher efficiency and better Service, Kim thinks its not enough. He believes that the existing business model is fragmented, users and content creators are the driving force, and the value lies in the network effect of the entire platform. These companies that rely on a large-scale user base to survive, but have gained huge gains in the market. Valuation, and users and content creators have almost nothing. Service platforms or third-party intermediaries charge high commissions and fees, resulting in a huge and unequal income gap between creators and them. It also causing users to bear high content consumption costs. Therefore, he designed the website to motivate the UGC creation model, and encourage uploaders to upload continuously and jointly build the network. But in fact, users seem to benefit from this part of the content, but the real creators do not. Due to copyright issues, a large number of creators works were pirated on the website, which also led to a decrease in the revenue of many companies. And reducing revenue and profits means that creators will lack the cost of the next creation and even reduce the enthusiasm of creators. In the issue of piracy, only consumers really benefit, and creators themselves do not benefit from piracy. According to data, after the website was shut down, the payment status of various paid media software generally increased by 6%-10% (Gregersen, 2020). This means that the website does have an impact on the normal entertainment market. At the same time, the extravagant life of the founder himself shows to a greater extent that the proceeds of this part of the website are used more for his personal, and even the funds obtained through illegal means are used to serve his personal life. The nature of this behavior does not effectively motivate creators but uses the speed and low threshold of the Internet to spread information to harm the interests of creators. In the book "Computer Ethics", Deborah Johnson (2014) believes that computers are widely used in business, civilian use, management, education, justice, medical care, and scientific research. In every environment, there are contradictions and conflicts between people's goals and interests, institutional goals, interpersonal relationships, and social norms. The purpose of studying computer ethics is to understand the ethical issues caused by computer information technology. He pointed out: "In this regard, the emergence of computer ethics research is to study human beings and society-our goals and values, our norms of behavior, the way we organize ourselves, the distribution of rights and responsibilities and so on. Some Americans Scholars believe that the application of computers directly reflects the actions and ideas of society. Computer ethics research can be used as a window into the society. In the "network society", social, political, and economic social forces are all active (Johnson, 2015). The most important feature of network technologies is their variability, and they can do almost anything. In the "virtual real" society of "network society", people's behavior involves the interests of individuals, enterprises, social groups and other social aspects. Computer ethics is established for the reasonable understanding and adjustment of the benefits arising from the application of information and network technology. In this case, Kim used the convenience of the computer to benefit himself. In this case, the responsibilities were not separated, and the person who should benefit did not benefit. In Kim's actions, he sacrificed the interests of real creators instead of protecting the interests of creators. The government needs to manage intellectual property rights and punish some companies that violate regulations. In order to protect the interests of true creators, the government needs to further regulate Internet piracy or infringement. Currently, Kim has started a new project called K.im. Every K.im content creator has its own encrypted content store. The store makes it a reality for creators to manage content, price and monetize it. The content placed in it will be double-encrypted and no one can see the creator. If the user wants to view the uploaded content, he needs to pay according to the creator's setting (Gregersen, 2020). The token KIM is issued based on Blockstream's Liquid Network. KIM is mainly used as a functional token to operate in the entire system. The risk of piracy of this software is very similar to that of Mega (Gregersen, 2020). For the government, more standardized and frequent inspections are required. Laws and supervision mechanisms related to courts also need to be continuously revised and updated in the development of the Internet.

This is actually a very serious behavior, which will cause people to question the price of genuine books, thus leading to the unsalable of genuine books or forced to sell in reduced copies. Thus, the phenomenon of "bad money drives out good money" is caused. There is a complete set of safety standards for book publishing, which has strict industry requirements for paper, ink, and printing.
