Kim Dotcom, born Kim Schmitz of West Germany, is the founder of the now-defunct file hosting giant Megaupload.com. Megaupload was a massive cyberlocker in the early 21st century, hosting a massive amount of user-uploaded media from all over the world. Kim claimed Megaupload was to remove any illegally uploaded copyrighted material when notified to do so, as per its terms of use. However, Megaupload was alleged by US authorities to have generated more than $175M in criminal proceeds and caused more than $500M in harm to copyright owners. In the eyes of the US Department of Justice, Kim Schmitz was a criminal who was guilty of criminal copyright infringement, money laundering, racketeering, and wire fraud. However, in the eyes of others, such as the popular Hacktivist group Anonymous, Kim Schmitz was an internet hero who took the first major leap into the unchartered territory of a free internet space (in terms of freedom, not price). There is a heavy debate around the ethics involved behind Kim Schmitzs actions. Some may argue he was a hero, while others may deem him the villain. Both sides have merit to their arguments, and Kims actions pose an interesting ethical question of whether he was within his rights to create Megaupload.com. Under the concept of negative and positive rights, one may argue Kim Schmitz had the negative right to create Megaupload as a regular file hosting site. As stated in its terms of use, Megaupload would remove any content found to violate copyright law when notified. However, this poses a logistical issue once Megaupload grew to over 50 million daily users at its peak [1]. How would Megaupload successfully screen the uploads of 50 million users each day for copyright infringement? These users agree to the terms of use when they log on to the site. The issue here was that users did not have to create an account; they could anonymously upload any media they had in mere minutes at the click of a few buttons. It was within Megauploads negative rights to provide a legitimate file hosting service that attempted to restrict copyright infringement. The positive rights of the users would be to provide assurance for Megaupload that they would commit to their agreement against uploading anything that was prohibited. Megauploads positive rights would be to enforce these agreements if users went rogue and disobeyed the terms of use, while the users negative rights would be the right to upload any media they had the rights to that didnt infringe on any copyrighted material. In theory, Megaupload would have provided an immensely valuable service to the world if both parties adhered the supposed terms of use established by Megaupload. Unfortunately, this was most certainly not the case, and authorities were forced to intervene. Megaupload sounded like a phenomenal idea on paper; users would be able to upload files to the internet quickly and easily. Anyone would be able to instantly access these shared files no matter their location in the world, as long as they had an internet connection with the corresponding link to the file. Megaupload did not offer a search function, so only users with the proper link could access the file being shared. This was near-revolutionary when it was first introduced in 2005. However, this soon began to spiral out of control due to many factors. One main driving factor behind the US Department of Justices decision to indict Kim Schmitz for the creation of Megaupload was the fact that Megaupload paid its users money based on how often their files were downloaded [2]. This payment model enticed users to upload heavily Page 2 sought-after media that would generate the most downloads at the time, which would most often be pirated versions of the newest movies or TV shows to come out. With over 1 billion page views, 180 million registered users, and 25 petabytes of files shared [3], it was inevitable that copyrighted material would run rampant on Megaupload. After all, it would attract the most file downloads, thus making the uploader the most money. This is where I believe Kim Dotcom to be more of a criminal than a hero. The idea of a site where users may freely share files they had the rights to among their peers would have been an extraordinary site, especially around the early times of the internet when Megaupload was created. By not actively enforcing his terms of use in a stricter manner, Kim Dotcom was a blatant enabler to copyright infringement. Had he put more strict controls in place to prevent said activity, I would consider him to be a hero responsible for one of the first great internet sites to exist. Many others may see Kim Dotcom in a different light. The hacktivist group Anonymous launched their largest attack ever in retaliation for the US Department of Justice shutting down Megaupload [4]. They supported the idea behind Megaupload; a place where users may upload files freely without restrictions. Personally, I could see the appeal to this argument. A truly free, unrestricted, and uncensored file sharing website on the internet used by people in countries all over the world would have been ground-breaking. It would truly be a pinnacle of the internet, symbolizing the freedom of speech in digital form. Censorship is a heavily debated ethical topic among governments and citizens alike. By having a website such as Megaupload unhinged by geographical borders and governments, it would unite people of all different demographics. In this regard, I do not consider Kim Dotcom a defined hero nor criminal. I fully support the idea of Megaupload in theory, but I do not support its execution. Allowing mass amounts of copyrighted material to be uploaded without intervention is where Kim Dotcom went wrong and paints him as a criminal. Governments should most definitely intervene if someone such as Kim Dotcom is directly profiting as well as siphoning revenue from copyright owners by facilitating and outright enabling copyright infringement activity. Mass amounts of time, money, and resources are put into content creation that is intended to generate a return for the creators; Kim Dotcom bypassed the investment portion of content creation and instead, in financial terms, became a broker-dealer of sorts without the rights or legality of being one. If Megaupload was successful in its intended use on paper, I think it would have surpassed its status as a simple file sharing site. Uniting people from all over the world through shared media is something that is hard to accomplish even today. Common sites like Facebook are banned and censored in countries such as China, so there is no one central unregulated and uncensored website for all kinds of media spanning the world. Had Megaupload succeeded in its execution, the world would be very different, especially today when unity is something countries such as the US lacks with its recent divisive nature of events. Exposing users to different cultures through file hosting transcends any physical effects, allowing for people of all ethnicities to experience media from anywhere they would like. This would have a direct effect on racism and xenophobia, as the majority of people only consume censored media that is tailored to Page 3 themselves in their respective countries. The potential for something great was present, but the execution was not. Page 4

list.string: Janiece Mary Padilla In the technology industry businesses are linked to copyright laws, in several ways these relations can be affected and lead to unfavorable outcomes. Copyright infringement is one of the greatest problems faced in the industry of technology and entertainment. People need to understand what copyright laws are and know how their lives can be impacted by illegal acts such as copyright infringement. It is important to recognize that copyright infringement will impact the way businesses interact with customers and government organizations. For example, the controversial case involving Megaupload and the founder Kim Schmitz will be analyzed to demonstrate how copyright infringement affects those involved. Negative rights and positive rights of this case will be discussed from an ethical point of view. The two key issues to be addressed are how the founders reputation was influenced by the results of the case and what authorities should do when industry leaders participate in illegal activities such as copyright infringement. These narratives will help analyze copyright infringement and how it impacted the case of Megaupload and its creator. Some correlations can be drawn between different scenarios and this case, which can provide a simple viewpoint on how infringement of copyright impacts corporations, government agencies, and consumers. The case involving Megaupload and its creator Kim Schmitz has gone through highs and lows. This particular case has gained national attention with the founder Kim Schmitz known as Dotcom fighting deportation to the United States because of his actions.[1] The creator of the infamous Megaupload file sharing website has been trying to appeal this ruling and has been adamant that the website allowed people to upload files to the cloud and at the time only small files could be attached to emails. This is an admission to what the website was meant to do according to the founder. From an ethical point of view, because he had these negative rights, Kim "Dotcom" was empowered to build a website with the ability to exchange files and not have interference with government agencies. If the situation is seen from this angle, then he exercised his liberty by creating this website and he was okay to do so. When the government stopped the use of the website and its content, his negative rights were violated. The positive rights here are the government's obligation to prevent the use of the website. The website caused significant losses to businesses in the entertainment industry. In general, work was copied and circulated illegally, and this was notappropriatebehaviorfor the government to have promoted. This view outweighs his negative rights because ultimately, he was harming businesses and breaking laws. All of the businesses involvedworked hard to get their content available on the market and it was not right for someone to benefit from their work simply because the opportunity was there. In the technology sector, Kim "Dotcom" can be seen as a pioneer, and a criminal at the same time. He was able to influence others because the industry had a loophole. It is a case that has been seen around the world, and one that has been popular because his website was very popular on the internet at one instance. Kim Schmitzs attitude is surprising, he was able to launch Mega.nz a new site that has the ability to provide encoded unidentified cloud storage while this case was ongoing. In cases that deal with copyright infringement, government departments around the world should hold people responsible for facilitating criminal activity. The government should also hold the people accountable; it is not fair to all of the parties involved. In this situation there are people involved in these activities that are not held responsible. Fines for the leaders should be considered in court andthe users that actively participated in the act should be subjected to a small penalty. Certainly, punishment willvarybetween countries, all countrieshave different lawsregarding the internet and copyrighthence interpretations around the world would be different. Copyright infringement not only extends to cyber-related industries but may also occur in art-related industries. For example, there have been cases that relate to artwork being copied or mimicked between artists. Sometimes these cases result in the defendants actions not being qualified as fair use.[3] For something to be considered fair use there are four factors to consider, and when the case involving the Barack Obama poster went to court, they determined the nature of use of the photograph that was copied. This case presented a unique outlook into how paying homage to another persons art can be a delicate matter if done without permission. This event is comparable to the Megaupload case presented above, since the parties did not have the owner's permission to copy or share the content ultimately both cases resulted in the individual being wrong. [3] According to AP News the Fairey versus The Associated Press case resulted in sentencing for the individual involved. A photograph taken was misused and distributed and resulted in unfavorable outcomes for the artist. This simple example is similar to the Megaupload case because the person involved also benefited from the work that was copied and did not give recognition to the original creator. This shows that regardless of what type of industry someone is in copyright rules always apply and the original creators of the work should be cited. In conclusion, violation of copyright is a serious matter that results in consequences for the parties involved. Governments can issue punishments or consequences that may vary depending on the circumstance and location of incidence at the time. In every situation that involves copyright infringement the truth and facts will be recognized and reflect in the outcome. In the industry of technology and entertainment, individuals and governments are all affected by the actions of an individual and those involved. It is important to take notes of cases like the one mentioned above as they can provide great insight on how copyright works in different industries. Ultimately, Kim Schmitz was not extradited to the United States however his case will be always be important because it provides the perspectives of all the parties involved when dealing with a situation as such. Copyright infringement should always be taken seriously, and originality must be highlighted in every work that is done. Individuals that partake in illegal activities should always be held accountable for their actions. As the industry grows there is more hope in knowing that individuals will strive to do the right things when it comes to copyright infringement. Functions Megaupload is the leading provider of online storage and web hosting services. People can enjoy cheap and convenient online storage, upload, and download services on Megaupload. Millions of people from all walks of life in many countries are using it. Students, professional businessmen, mothers, doctors, plumbers, insurance salesmen, mortgage brokers. Its user base is very broad, so it has a large market. Negative impact Megaupload has encroached on the interests of many people. In January 2012 Dotcom and six other executives of Megaupload were indicted in an American court on five counts of to commit racketeering, copyright infringement, and . (Erik, 2012) The site allows people to share resources publicly. If the downloaded movie is used for other commercial purposes, there will be more losses. Every movie is owned by the copyright owner, and movie theaters and online viewing sites legally buy movie rights. The advertised websites of The 'content hosting site, Megaupload.com, is advertised as having more than one billion visits to The site, more than 150 million registered users, Fifty million daily visitors and accounting for four percent of the total traffic on the Internet. The harm caused by the Conspiracy's criminal conduct to copyright holders is well in excess of $500 million. The conspirators allegedly earned more than $175 million in illegal profits through advertising revenue and selling premium memberships. (Office of public Affairs, 2012) In addition to its impact on studio revenues, Megaupload also affects the order of the film market. According to the statistics, online sales and rentals of films have increased by 6-10% since Megaupload was closed. It is a new illegal way to share movie resources on the Internet, so people may also reduce the number of times to go to the cinema. Advantages The fact that the site has such a large customer base suggests that it has a strong appeal. It makes it easier for people to see the movies they want to see and spend less money on them. The site is great for users, and it exists as an alternative to watching movies in some traditional ways. In addition, people can search through this website to find some movie resources that are not easy to find. It's like a movie that has been cut in some places or not shown publicly. It also includes pornographic and violent films, which are banned in many places. This is a new way of media, just like Tik Tok is changing the way media works now. In new media, interpersonal communication, mass communication and mass communication show a trend of integration and integration of multiple functions. Due to the convergence of media, the information transmission of new media is characterized by high speed, high quality, excessive quantity, diversification and wide range. The introduction and extensive use of a new media can reconstruct a series of situations, change people's lives and thoughts, and require a series of new social and economic behaviors. Character evaluation Megaupload broke traditional boundaries and created a popular new approach. The success of the site is enough to show that it exists as expected. This website provides a good sharing platform to meet people's needs. Seeing the popularity of the site at the time was enough to show that it was not a mistake. But the only problem is the infringement on the interests of the film studios. It's like a farmer's hard-earned crops being eaten by pesky birds. For the crew and actors who have struggled to make films, this is not what they want to see. For this reason, and because the number of users of the site is still growing, Megaupload must be legally sanctioned. Dotcom is a very brave man because he knew how it would turn out. People can also make money from the site, as long as the number of hits and download rates reach a certain level, they can make money from it. So, it's a great experience for users. Internet piracy Computer users and Internet service providers shall bear the corresponding civil liability for infringing the civil rights and interests of the state, the collective or others through the Internet. In recent years, with the rapid development of the network era, many new problems are becoming more and more prominent. In China, although a series of relevant laws and regulations, judicial interpretations and administrative rules have been successively issued by the legislative branch to regulate online behaviors and protect citizens' legal rights in the online environment to some extent. However, compared with the ever-changing situation of network development, there are still many deficiencies in the existing laws concerning network infringement. With the rapid development and popularization of the Internet, it is urgent to formulate relevant laws and regulations to regulate all kinds of Internet behaviors. Strengthen the training of professional personnel In addition to legal means, the application of advanced technical means is also indispensable to control network infringement. In order to better protect civil rights, effectively prevent the occurrence of network infringement, the complexity of network infringement puts forward higher requirements for network management talents. More interdisciplinary talents with legal knowledge, professional computer and network management are needed. To make a large number of compound information network management talents stand out in the cause of information network play a strong force. Conclusion In general, Megaupload has now been sanctioned by the law for being an illegal site. Legal and moral considerations should be considered before interests. Although it is illegal, it has a large number of users and a wide market. This shows that this is a trend of media platform development but need to pay attention to more network security incidents. Openness and freedom are the charm of the Internet. But, as George Bernard Shaw said, "Freedom means responsibility! A free, democratic, and rule-of-law society is the result of the coexistence and complementarity between individual freedom and public responsibility. Abstract Copyright infringement affects the technology and entertainment industry in many ways. In the case where Megaupload is the main controversy, it is evident that copyright infringement affects the founder and governments involved. There will be an emphasis throughout the essay on how the founder was affected by this case. There will be suggestions on what things should be done in future cases of this matter. In addition, an example presented will provide an insight into how other industries can be affected by copyright infringement.

Megaupload, was the most popular online cloud hard disk service in the world. It was built by Kim Schmitz in 2005. The site once had more than 150m registered users and 50 million daily visitors. Megaupload used to be the 13th most visited website on the Internet. Many users upload their files or download files that sheared by other users. Because many users of the website often share the files that offense the copyright or privacy. Also, the way Megaupload profit is by commercial advertisement. These advertisements were delivered to the downloaders. While some files were less popular than the others. These files would be deleted by the server without any warning to the uploaders or potential downloaders. Therefore, Megaupload faced many charges which include illegal separation of copyright protected production. However, hidden illegal behaviors were commons for Megaupload users. Finally, in 2012, the largest used internet hard disk was forced to be closed by the United States Department of Justice. The reason is: Megaupload operates differently from other file storage businesses. The indictment argues that the following design elements of its operating model are evidence of criminal intent and risk. Kim Schmitz was arrest by the FBI. His service due to the movie studios and record companies lost more than $500 million and more than $175 million in illegal profits by encouraging users to save and share copyrighted content. In 2016, Kim Schmitz was released, he openly announced that he wants to restart another upload disk service. The case of Megaupload reflects some conflict of human rights. The companies that hold copyrights of their products have a positive right to be protected from illegal separation and copy. They think Megaupload is a criminal who brought enormous economic loss; they need to destroy the online storage service like Megaupload. However, Megaupload users also have their own right to use Megaupload. The users have the negative right to handle their personal item or wealth freely. Other people should not prevent them to use Megaupload even the file is not lawful, because that is personal stuff. It is clear that people always have something that would not likely to be seen by others. Also considering the freedom of speech, the way of people sharing should not be limit. The ICCPR, full name isInternational Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. It claimed: Everyone shall have the right to freedom of expression; this right shall include freedom to seek, receive and impart information and ideas of all kinds, regard less of frontiers, either orally, in writing or in print, in the form of art, or through any other media of his choice. One thing needs to be noticed is that Megaupload is a worldwide service. It not only charged by the law of the United State, but also apply to the law of other countries. Overall, the conflict between users and dissenters is based on requirement of different benefits. There is a question of if Kim Schmitz is a hero or a criminal. The answer is swing between different groups. His Megaupload made a lot of users convenient with sharing the files and store the files without the trouble of carrying a hard disk. But there were many people uploaded illegal files that treated the profit of the others. On the other hand, Megaupload is a forward, innovative network service. The cloud storage was becoming the main current of mobile storage. It is not eligible to say Kim Schmitz made a total lawbreaking company. Generally, Megaupload have positive influence with network communication. Then the negative influence is facilitating illegal activity. If the uploading function have more regulation, some cloud storage platform Megaupload would be much better for internet surrounding. As a service which helped illegal activity, there are two kinds of standard to judge peoples responsibility. In the aspect of law, A person is criminally responsible for the facilitation of a felony, if, knowing that another intends to commit a specific felony, but without the intent required for criminal responsibility the person knowingly furnishes substantial assistance in the commission of the felony.. Clearly, Kim Schmitzs target is not for help people to crime, what he wants just make money from his service. Therefore, government cannot punish him without a critical evidence of helping illegal activities. However, in the ethical aspect. his behavior selectively ignored the measures which participate to prevent the illegal or criminal activities. Therefore, Kim Schmitz should be punished, but the method should be concentrated on economic range. Such as penalty and suspension of business. Different governments and law enforcement agencies have different ways to monitor the cloud storage service market. There is a familiar example in the east of the world called Baidu Netdisk. Like Megaupload, Baidu Netdisk is a cloud storage service which is popular in China at now. However, Baidu Netdisk is a free service and their main profit is from purchasing the cloud space. Baidu Netdisk have different way to benefits and it also facing the charge of privacy issue. There is a report of how Baidu company triggered an uproar from users: Imagine this: You sign up for a cloud storage service thinking youll only be using the companys servers. But then without asking, your provider not only takes up your computers storage space, but also uses your internet bandwidth to distribute files. This is what recently happened to users of Baidu Cloud, or Baidu Wangpan, when users were enrolled in a new incentive program by default. Users say they were offered award points in exchange for the use of up to 1MB/s of their internet upload bandwidth and 5GB of storage space for seven hours a day. Users can disable the function, but only if they go into settings and uncheck the option themselves. Chinese related government department forced Baidu to close the net disk service and reform the server organization. Everything seen was in a right trail since the government involved into the reformation. Baidu Netdisk became a membership liked platform. None VIP users need to pay for the download or upload speed instead occupying others bandwidth. Nonetheless, there were other disputes from the users. Because government let Baidu set up an inside function that detect weather the file contains illegal elements by human censors. Baidu Netdisk users are still be monitoring at now. So, the government over-involved into the market is also not a good idea. The best way that regulates the cloud storage market is complex. After all, cloud storage is a fashion, popular service over the network. In the 21th century, there are no one can stop the wheel of improvements because one day the mobile hard disk will be weed out by the new technology of the internet. Indeed, there are so many people holding bad thoughts with using cloud disk services. But there will be one day, the technique of filtering the illegal files uploading or sharing which is satisfied for every healthy users. Abstract Megaupload is an online upload and web storage site, people need to recharge their membership to use the site, this is a huge amount of illegal income. Megaupload operated from Hong Kong and New Zealand, with servers in several countries, and had 180 million registered users. This website violates the copyright of the film, thus causing great loss to the copyright owners. Federal prosecutors have accused it of costing copyright holders more than $500m (320m) in lost revenue. (BBC News, 2012) Key words: illegal income, copyright, film Introduction Megaupload used to be a very popular website with a lot of users using it. The reason why the site has so many users is that it satisfies the demand of many people to watch movies online. It combines many functions, making it easy for users to find what they want to see and saving money. But in doing so, it infringes on the film's copyright and damages the studios. Users could upload movies, music and other content to the site and share with others, a practice the U.S. considers copyright infringement. (Colin, 2016)

Megaupload is a well-known online network hard disk service provider. The software can upload large files up to 1GB, save for three months. It has an extremely wide range of users worldwide. Megaupload was founded in 2005. The number of registered users of the site has exceeded 150 million, while the number of daily visitors reached 50 million. Megaupload was once the 13th most visited website on the Internet (Danaher and Smith, 2014). However, due to the spread of a large number of piracy on Megaupload, on January 19, 2012, the US Department of Justice and the Federal Bureau of Investigation shut down Megaupload.com, the world-renowned sharing website. The founder also went to jail because of the incident. The indictment argues that Megaupload differs from other file storage business activities in the way it operates (Danaher and Smith, 2014). The indictment believes that the following design elements in its operating mode are evidence of its criminal intent and risk. Because most users do not have significant private storage capabilities on this website. The more downloaded files will be kept. At the same time, the paid users of the software account for only a small percentage, and the commercial benefits of the software largely depend on advertising. And the website guides users to locate infringing content on the site, share infringing content with others, and even part of the content involves illegal content such as child pornography. Accounts that commit infringements on the site will not be blocked, and the site just uses incentive programs to encourage users to upload more popular files. Even in the court documents, Megaupload is suspected of money laundering. In 2013, the founder was released from prison and Kim Dotcom has created a new site Mega. Official service to the outside world on January 19, 2013. The new platform built by Dotcom this time has made some rectifications compared to MegaUpload, especially in terms of data. Once the website was released, a large number of old users registered and uploaded users. According to reports, the Mega website has received more than 150 copyright infringement warnings in a short period of time. In addition, a third-party search engine was also blocked 24 hours after the release. . Since it was once banned due to piracy issues, Mega is currently very cautious on this issue. Last week, Mega has received more than 150 infringement warnings from copyright owners, but no copyright owners have filed a lawsuit . I think in this incident, the founder Kim was essentially a criminal. Mega has different functions for different subjects. Kim claims to have established a website from the perspective of content creators in order to allow creators themselves to obtain huge profits. As the Internet makes the marginal cost of content and information dissemination close to zero, huge demand has given birth to many unicorns with high market value, such as Netflix and Spotify (Peukert et al, 2017). Although these service-oriented platforms provide users and creators with higher efficiency and better Service, Kim thinks its not enough. He believes that the existing business model is fragmented, users and content creators are the driving force, and the value lies in the network effect of the entire platform. These companies that rely on a large-scale user base to survive, but have gained huge gains in the market. Valuation, and users and content creators have almost nothing. Service platforms or third-party intermediaries charge high commissions and fees, resulting in a huge and unequal income gap between creators and them. It also causing users to bear high content consumption costs. Therefore, he designed the website to motivate the UGC creation model, and encourage uploaders to upload continuously and jointly build the network. But in fact, users seem to benefit from this part of the content, but the real creators do not. Due to copyright issues, a large number of creators works were pirated on the website, which also led to a decrease in the revenue of many companies. And reducing revenue and profits means that creators will lack the cost of the next creation and even reduce the enthusiasm of creators. In the issue of piracy, only consumers really benefit, and creators themselves do not benefit from piracy. According to data, after the website was shut down, the payment status of various paid media software generally increased by 6%-10% (Gregersen, 2020). This means that the website does have an impact on the normal entertainment market. At the same time, the extravagant life of the founder himself shows to a greater extent that the proceeds of this part of the website are used more for his personal, and even the funds obtained through illegal means are used to serve his personal life. The nature of this behavior does not effectively motivate creators but uses the speed and low threshold of the Internet to spread information to harm the interests of creators. In the book "Computer Ethics", Deborah Johnson (2014) believes that computers are widely used in business, civilian use, management, education, justice, medical care, and scientific research. In every environment, there are contradictions and conflicts between people's goals and interests, institutional goals, interpersonal relationships, and social norms. The purpose of studying computer ethics is to understand the ethical issues caused by computer information technology. He pointed out: "In this regard, the emergence of computer ethics research is to study human beings and society-our goals and values, our norms of behavior, the way we organize ourselves, the distribution of rights and responsibilities and so on. Some Americans Scholars believe that the application of computers directly reflects the actions and ideas of society. Computer ethics research can be used as a window into the society. In the "network society", social, political, and economic social forces are all active (Johnson, 2015). The most important feature of network technologies is their variability, and they can do almost anything. In the "virtual real" society of "network society", people's behavior involves the interests of individuals, enterprises, social groups and other social aspects. Computer ethics is established for the reasonable understanding and adjustment of the benefits arising from the application of information and network technology. In this case, Kim used the convenience of the computer to benefit himself. In this case, the responsibilities were not separated, and the person who should benefit did not benefit. In Kim's actions, he sacrificed the interests of real creators instead of protecting the interests of creators. The government needs to manage intellectual property rights and punish some companies that violate regulations. In order to protect the interests of true creators, the government needs to further regulate Internet piracy or infringement. Currently, Kim has started a new project called K.im. Every K.im content creator has its own encrypted content store. The store makes it a reality for creators to manage content, price and monetize it. The content placed in it will be double-encrypted and no one can see the creator. If the user wants to view the uploaded content, he needs to pay according to the creator's setting (Gregersen, 2020). The token KIM is issued based on Blockstream's Liquid Network. KIM is mainly used as a functional token to operate in the entire system. The risk of piracy of this software is very similar to that of Mega (Gregersen, 2020). For the government, more standardized and frequent inspections are required. Laws and supervision mechanisms related to courts also need to be continuously revised and updated in the development of the Internet.

Kim Dotcom, born Kim Schmitz of West Germany, is the founder of the now-defunct file hosting giant Megaupload.com. Megaupload was a massive cyberlocker in the early 21st century, hosting a massive amount of user-uploaded media from all over the world. Kim claimed Megaupload was to remove any illegally uploaded copyrighted material when notified to do so, as per its terms of use. However, Megaupload was alleged by US authorities to have generated more than $175M in criminal proceeds and caused more than $500M in harm to copyright owners. In the eyes of the US Department of Justice, Kim Schmitz was a criminal who was guilty of criminal copyright infringement, money laundering, racketeering, and wire fraud. However, in the eyes of others, such as the popular Hacktivist group Anonymous, Kim Schmitz was an internet hero who took the first major leap into the unchartered territory of a free internet space (in terms of freedom, not price). There is a heavy debate around the ethics involved behind Kim Schmitzs actions. Some may argue he was a hero, while others may deem him the villain. Both sides have merit to their arguments, and Kims actions pose an interesting ethical question of whether he was within his rights to create Megaupload.com. Under the concept of negative and positive rights, one may argue Kim Schmitz had the negative right to create Megaupload as a regular file hosting site. As stated in its terms of use, Megaupload would remove any content found to violate copyright law when notified. However, this poses a logistical issue once Megaupload grew to over 50 million daily users at its peak [1]. How would Megaupload successfully screen the uploads of 50 million users each day for copyright infringement? These users agree to the terms of use when they log on to the site. The issue here was that users did not have to create an account; they could anonymously upload any media they had in mere minutes at the click of a few buttons. It was within Megauploads negative rights to provide a legitimate file hosting service that attempted to restrict copyright infringement. The positive rights of the users would be to provide assurance for Megaupload that they would commit to their agreement against uploading anything that was prohibited. Megauploads positive rights would be to enforce these agreements if users went rogue and disobeyed the terms of use, while the users negative rights would be the right to upload any media they had the rights to that didnt infringe on any copyrighted material. In theory, Megaupload would have provided an immensely valuable service to the world if both parties adhered the supposed terms of use established by Megaupload. Unfortunately, this was most certainly not the case, and authorities were forced to intervene. Megaupload sounded like a phenomenal idea on paper; users would be able to upload files to the internet quickly and easily. Anyone would be able to instantly access these shared files no matter their location in the world, as long as they had an internet connection with the corresponding link to the file. Megaupload did not offer a search function, so only users with the proper link could access the file being shared. This was near-revolutionary when it was first introduced in 2005. However, this soon began to spiral out of control due to many factors. One main driving factor behind the US Department of Justices decision to indict Kim Schmitz for the creation of Megaupload was the fact that Megaupload paid its users money based on how often their files were downloaded [2]. This payment model enticed users to upload heavily Page 2 sought-after media that would generate the most downloads at the time, which would most often be pirated versions of the newest movies or TV shows to come out. With over 1 billion page views, 180 million registered users, and 25 petabytes of files shared [3], it was inevitable that copyrighted material would run rampant on Megaupload. After all, it would attract the most file downloads, thus making the uploader the most money. This is where I believe Kim Dotcom to be more of a criminal than a hero. The idea of a site where users may freely share files they had the rights to among their peers would have been an extraordinary site, especially around the early times of the internet when Megaupload was created. By not actively enforcing his terms of use in a stricter manner, Kim Dotcom was a blatant enabler to copyright infringement. Had he put more strict controls in place to prevent said activity, I would consider him to be a hero responsible for one of the first great internet sites to exist. Many others may see Kim Dotcom in a different light. The hacktivist group Anonymous launched their largest attack ever in retaliation for the US Department of Justice shutting down Megaupload [4]. They supported the idea behind Megaupload; a place where users may upload files freely without restrictions. Personally, I could see the appeal to this argument. A truly free, unrestricted, and uncensored file sharing website on the internet used by people in countries all over the world would have been ground-breaking. It would truly be a pinnacle of the internet, symbolizing the freedom of speech in digital form. Censorship is a heavily debated ethical topic among governments and citizens alike. By having a website such as Megaupload unhinged by geographical borders and governments, it would unite people of all different demographics. In this regard, I do not consider Kim Dotcom a defined hero nor criminal. I fully support the idea of Megaupload in theory, but I do not support its execution. Allowing mass amounts of copyrighted material to be uploaded without intervention is where Kim Dotcom went wrong and paints him as a criminal. Governments should most definitely intervene if someone such as Kim Dotcom is directly profiting as well as siphoning revenue from copyright owners by facilitating and outright enabling copyright infringement activity. Mass amounts of time, money, and resources are put into content creation that is intended to generate a return for the creators; Kim Dotcom bypassed the investment portion of content creation and instead, in financial terms, became a broker-dealer of sorts without the rights or legality of being one. If Megaupload was successful in its intended use on paper, I think it would have surpassed its status as a simple file sharing site. Uniting people from all over the world through shared media is something that is hard to accomplish even today. Common sites like Facebook are banned and censored in countries such as China, so there is no one central unregulated and uncensored website for all kinds of media spanning the world. Had Megaupload succeeded in its execution, the world would be very different, especially today when unity is something countries such as the US lacks with its recent divisive nature of events. Exposing users to different cultures through file hosting transcends any physical effects, allowing for people of all ethnicities to experience media from anywhere they would like. This would have a direct effect on racism and xenophobia, as the majority of people only consume censored media that is tailored to Page 3 themselves in their respective countries. The potential for something great was present, but the execution was not. Page 4
